WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:09.000 --> 00:00:22.000
13. My name is John Bitmer and I'm here in Denmark, South Carolina with videographer John Bishop to interview Dr. Dr. Cleveland L. Sellers Jr and the President of Voorhees College.

00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:31.000
This interview will become part of the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture in Washington, DC.

00:00:31.000 --> 00:00:36.000
Dr. Sellers were delighted to be here today and we thank you for taking the time to talk with us.

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Thank you, thank you.

00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:46.000
I would like to start with your early childhood. You were born and raised right here in Denmark, weren't you?

00:00:46.000 --> 00:01:01.000
Born and raised in Denmark, the irony is that it's been pretty much a complete circle for me and that I started out here as a mascot for the college in when I was three years old.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:11.000
And I came back in 2008 as President of the college so it's a very interesting experience returning home.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:17.000
What was it like growing up in Denmark? Tell us something about your childhood, your family?

00:01:17.000 --> 00:01:29.000
Well, the first bit of information is that the college here was the center, a cultural center of an educational center for the community.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:42.000
I actually went to high school on this campus, the state of South Carolina rather than building a high school for black students, paid for his tuition for each student.

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:55.000
So all the students in this area when they started eighth grade, ninth grade, tenth grade and 11th grade, I'm sorry, ninth grade, tenth grade, 11th and 12th, they would come to this campus.

00:01:55.000 --> 00:02:05.000
And this campus was, this school was actually founded by a woman 23 years old who was a graduate of Tuskegee.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:15.000
And so she used the Tuskegee model in terms of building educational institutions and came to Denmark to find, found her school.

00:02:15.000 --> 00:02:26.000
She had a couple of the efforts in South Carolina but they were all two cases of Austin and one of Malphee's and so she ended up here in Denmark.

00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:34.000
So the school is made under the Tuskegee Booker T. Washington Industrial Education Model.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:40.000
So it is just that kind of philosophy was very prevalent here.

00:02:40.000 --> 00:02:59.000
Even though you had the, the Du Bois influence also at Voorhees College, it was the kind of bill yourself up, educate yourself, have faith in your community and those kinds of ideals that grew out of Booker T. Washington.

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:04.000
So that was the kind of community I grew up in. It was segregated, I mean, rigidly segregated.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:06.000
Race relations.

00:03:06.000 --> 00:03:14.000
Race relations were as a segregated community in the South all throughout the South.

00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:22.000
And that is separation in terms of schools, social activities, almost complete separation up and down the ranks.

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.000
There were no buses so we didn't have segregation on the buses.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:36.000
But we did have in the theater even in terms of patronizing stores.

00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:46.000
There were certain things that you had to buy without actually having an opportunity to use a dressing room and that kind of thing to see if it fit and that all of that kind of stuff.

00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:51.000
What was the roughly the ratio of break down between black and white at the time?

00:03:51.000 --> 00:03:59.000
Denmark has been majority black for a long period of time and it was majority black at that point.

00:03:59.000 --> 00:04:06.000
But all of the official offices were held by whites, Superintendent of the School School Board.

00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:10.000
I was in the economy back then. What were people doing for a living?

00:04:10.000 --> 00:04:18.000
Back then there was a pretty busy kind of and a live and well economy.

00:04:18.000 --> 00:04:27.000
We had three railroads that actually came through Denmark. That was a unique environment in which we kind of grew up in.

00:04:27.000 --> 00:04:34.000
And there was a pickle plan, a furniture plan, a bowling, a cocoa, a bowling company and all those kinds of things.

00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:47.000
When the railroads went away and when the economy reverted back to pretty much agricultural, rural agricultural economy, those jobs also went away.

00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:55.000
And so you had a decreasing of the population since the period of desegregation.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:59.000
Many whites moved out of the community.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:06.000
The schools in Denmark actually integrated, desegregated around 1972.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:11.000
So you're talking about some 18 years after brown. That was resistance to desegregation.

00:05:11.000 --> 00:05:15.000
Did you see those students leave the schools when desegregation came or used to?

00:05:15.000 --> 00:05:23.000
Yes, sir. Over the last 10 years it's been about 98, 99% African-American in the school.

00:05:23.000 --> 00:05:25.000
Pretty typical in many areas.

00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:41.000
But now the unique part about the Voorhees connection and the school connection was that there were a lot of cultural incentives and there were a lot of educational opportunities that were afforded students.

00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:53.000
The teachers provide a certain respect for education and dignified education and also provide nurturing that built up these.

00:05:53.000 --> 00:06:00.000
I guess values and principles, the importance of education, the importance of faith and the importance of service.

00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:07.000
And so we learned that as we went along, we learned about the Harlem Renaissance and literature and art.

00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:18.000
We learned about the importance of actually developing skills going out and returning something to the community that nurtured you and actually got you started.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:31.000
Those kind of values were very important values for young African-Americans to have going out into this new world that was very soon become desegregated.

00:06:31.000 --> 00:06:43.000
The other was that we also were able to tie into the black press and we were able to read about and understand what was going on in Montgomery.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:46.000
You could discuss that in school, Emmett Till.

00:06:46.000 --> 00:06:48.000
What talk about that a minute?

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:53.000
You were, I think, 11 years old when Emmett Till was murdered in Mississippi.

00:06:53.000 --> 00:06:56.000
What kind of impact does that have on you?

00:06:56.000 --> 00:06:59.000
And I want to talk about your folks too.

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:09.000
Yeah, well, I was devastated by the fact that Emmett could have been me or any other black kid around that same age.

00:07:09.000 --> 00:07:12.000
And so I related to that very quickly.

00:07:12.000 --> 00:07:15.000
And we had discussions in our class about Emmett Till.

00:07:15.000 --> 00:07:20.000
I had a cover of the jet, took it to school, some other students had the same thing.

00:07:20.000 --> 00:07:23.000
And so we had rational discussions about it.

00:07:23.000 --> 00:07:27.000
And the question comes up, how do you address that?

00:07:27.000 --> 00:07:38.000
And I think for us, it was projected out that that would be our destiny to try to find remedies to a society that would allow that to happen.

00:07:38.000 --> 00:07:46.000
It would condone that and would actually free those who were responsible for that murder.

00:07:46.000 --> 00:07:55.000
And I think that that was a way in which we actually got away from revenge and hatred and those kinds of things.

00:07:55.000 --> 00:08:06.000
We talked about how we were going to use Emmett Till to build on that we would rectify in our work and in our effort.

00:08:06.000 --> 00:08:12.000
And the nasty that they tragedy that happened to Emmett Till.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:18.000
It just was, I've become obvious to me that you had a unique opportunity here in school to do these things.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:22.000
I mean, these kinds of discussions would not be going on in a specific class.

00:08:22.000 --> 00:08:29.000
And people would be teachers who were fired for something like that.

00:08:29.000 --> 00:08:30.000
Absolutely.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
In this rural outpost.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:33.000
That's right.

00:08:33.000 --> 00:08:45.000
And when the independence of the British colonies in Africa was taking place, we could actually relate to that.

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:56.000
And some of the professors at the institution related to Kwame Nkrumah because he was a graduate and a student at Lincoln University.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:00.000
So there was a kind of common thread here.

00:09:00.000 --> 00:09:07.000
So with Patrice Lumumba and the Congo and Kwame Nkrumah and Jomal, Kinyata and Kenya.

00:09:07.000 --> 00:09:10.000
Those kinds of discussions were very common place.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:14.000
And we did have students here from Africa.

00:09:14.000 --> 00:09:21.000
So they were able to actually bring news back through literature and dispatches in Africa.

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:28.000
And those things would show up in the campus news letter and newspaper that the students would actually put up.

00:09:28.000 --> 00:09:38.000
And so it was that kind of nurturing and that kind of educational environment that we came up in.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:45.000
Most of the students that graduated with me went on to college.

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:55.000
Some made a D2 and went to the home forces in order for them to get the GI bill so they could come back and go to school.

00:09:55.000 --> 00:10:05.000
And we were talking about probably in some way in the neighborhood of 85, 87% of the students who graduated from me went on to some kind of company.

00:10:05.000 --> 00:10:06.000
That's very high.

00:10:06.000 --> 00:10:07.000
That's very high.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:10.000
Tell us something about your books and your family.

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:25.000
My family, both natives of South Carolina, my mother comes from Abbeyville, South Carolina, which is up in the northern part of the state around Greenville and Anderson, South Carolina.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:29.000
She was in a family of eight sisters.

00:10:29.000 --> 00:10:44.000
And it was a large family. She lived on a large farm and they actually were farmers and they raised horses on that farm.

00:10:44.000 --> 00:10:50.000
And other things, but that was their primary focus.

00:10:50.000 --> 00:10:58.000
My father grew up in Denmark South Carolina and he graduated from high school in 1933.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:09.000
Education was very important to him because he was in Denmark and education was very important to all young African Americans in this community.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:18.000
He was an entrepreneur. He followed in the tradition and footsteps, the things that he had learned from the Book of T Washington influence at the school.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:36.000
So he was a farmer. He was not not real at all, but a rent built in rented houses and property. He drove care of anything that he could find a way in which he could actually generate some revenue from.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:52.000
He did that kind of thing. And the latest, the last thing major thing that he did was he built the motel. He understood the movement of people in and out and the need for the colleges that were here to do that kind of thing.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:54.000
And so that's what he did.

00:11:54.000 --> 00:12:06.000
My mother was an educator. She graduated from South Carolina State back, I think it was around the 20, 27, somewhere around that time.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:17.000
And she then went on to Hampton University and she got her masters and was able to, she got it in nutrition and English.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:27.000
And she was able to come back to South Carolina. She started at Voorhees College and worked here for about 20 years.

00:12:27.000 --> 00:12:37.000
And then she moved over to the technical and trade school for the state of South Carolina, which was also located here in Denmark.

00:12:37.000 --> 00:12:47.000
And she worked there for 15 years. And she had several years after graduating from South Carolina State teaching in high schools.

00:12:47.000 --> 00:13:04.000
So she was an educator and she also was very much a community organ in it and actually ran for a number of years when I was a young, a, a, a center that was built in in Denmark by donations and contributions.

00:13:04.000 --> 00:13:17.000
It's a Denmark Recreation Center. And she managed that all the way until she was much older and passed her retirement and she passed that off to another gentleman.

00:13:17.000 --> 00:13:33.000
But so in that she was very, much concerned about working with young ladies and actually helping them kind of grow up and find their way and empower them to, to be,

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:45.000
to take advantage of whatever educational opportunities they were and be good at what they did. So that's, yeah, I have a sister Gwendolyn. She was a year old and I was.

00:13:45.000 --> 00:13:56.000
I was born and my father was in the military in World War II. He was, he was stationed in France. And he was very proud of his, his work there.

00:13:56.000 --> 00:14:10.000
He, he, he had a business, a kind of cafe restaurant business that he, he left to go to fight. And he was in the motor pool, I think in France.

00:14:10.000 --> 00:14:22.000
And he went off and came back, met a lot of people, seemed to have created some good friendships as a result of his experience in France and that kind of thing.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:42.000
And he came back to Denmark and, and continued. My sister was born a year before me and she kind of grew up also with, without father being out of, for two years in, in the military.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:15:00.000
She went to school here to matriculate it through, went on and, and became a school teacher, master school teacher, a school counselor in New Jersey. And she was there for 30 years and had returned to, to South Carolina now.

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:04.000
Yes, was, was, uh, church very important in your family life?

00:15:04.000 --> 00:15:17.000
Church was very important in my family life and, uh, I had, I was a schism. You know, we, my mother was a, uh, was an A.M.E. when she was born and reared and as she grew up.

00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:30.000
And when she married my father, uh, he was a Baptist. So she then went to the Baptist Church. And when she came to work at Voorhees, Voorhees was affiliated with the Episcopal Church.

00:15:30.000 --> 00:15:39.000
And, uh, she and my, my sister and I, all affiliated with the Episcopal Church. And so she was there for a minute.

00:15:39.000 --> 00:15:55.000
And then, uh, in later in life after she retired, she went back to the A.M.E. Church. And so, uh, we remain in the Episcopal Church. We're, my sister and I, pretty, almost cradle Episcopalians.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:16:12.000
And, um, and, uh, I have been affiliated with the Episcopal Church from that time until now. There was stints in which, um, you know, I was doing other kinds of things and didn't have the same kind of affiliation that I had before after.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:35.000
But, uh, it has, it has been, even through the movement experience, uh, very much involved, uh, when I was at Howett at the Non-Valent Action Group, we used to meet at the, um, at the Episcopal Affiliated Youth Club, um, there at, at Howard University.

00:16:35.000 --> 00:16:48.000
And through my experiences with SNCC, we had at various and Sunday times, support from Episcopal Priests all over the country and all over the South. So, it's been a good, mm-hmm.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:50.000
We're back.

00:16:50.000 --> 00:16:51.000
Okay.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:17:02.000
Um, well, with this kind of background, it was naturally assumed, I think, that you were going to go to college, but the movement came along.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:09.000
And in February of 1960, the city began in Greensboro, North Carolina.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:13.000
And they, uh, spread to Denmark, South Carolina.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:14.000
Absolutely.

00:17:14.000 --> 00:17:15.000
Talk about that for a moment.

00:17:15.000 --> 00:17:22.000
Well, um, I, again, I'm a high school student and I'm here. I actually work in the student center.

00:17:22.000 --> 00:17:36.000
Um, I have my, um, my high school assistant principal, wife, runs the student center. So, she asked me if I'd work in and I do.

00:17:36.000 --> 00:17:45.000
And it's on February, February 1, 1960, the, uh, city ends, occurring in Greensboro, North Carolina.

00:17:45.000 --> 00:17:49.000
And the first night, it gets a blip on the news.

00:17:49.000 --> 00:18:03.000
The second night, it has a more time because the news is actually talking about the students and, uh, the kind of, uh, tactics that were being employed and what was going to happen and all that kind of thing.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:13.000
So the, the, uh, student center used to fill up every night for the nightly news to see what was going on in Greensboro.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:27.000
And so students actually began to, to talk about the sit-ins and begin to, uh, talk about having meetings and then what are we going to do and how are we going to do that?

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:43.000
Uh, and so I had the opportunity because they were in the center usually and they would start meeting in the Senate and they would go to other places because they felt like they needed to be kind of out of the sight of the administration because nobody knew how the administration was going to accept this.

00:18:43.000 --> 00:18:49.000
This was just a kind of, uh, students being really actively engaged in this process.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:56.000
So they decided to, uh, to do a demonstration themselves and they actually were a boat, a boat with that.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:10.000
They went to the president and asked the president, uh, because it's about two and a half, three, three miles downtown to the pharmacy if they could use the school bus in order for them to go to that.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:19.000
And, uh, the president agreed, yes. And, uh, so then the, the, the D day came, I think it was the Thursday.

00:19:19.000 --> 00:19:33.000
And the students were assembled and the president had been called by a number of the board of trustees who were local who said that they didn't think it was a good idea that he needed to not do the bus.

00:19:33.000 --> 00:19:39.000
And they were scared to the students from coming downtown. They didn't know what was going to happen and they were concerned.

00:19:39.000 --> 00:19:42.000
So, uh, he asked that the bus be withdrawn.

00:19:42.000 --> 00:19:51.000
Uh, I think that, uh, I would agree that he was a lot like Warmoth T. Gibbs who was the president of, uh, of A and T at that time.

00:19:51.000 --> 00:19:56.000
And his thing was was that I trust you and I trust your judgment to the students.

00:19:56.000 --> 00:20:02.000
But I am not going to be able to, to be openly supportive of your actions.

00:20:02.000 --> 00:20:07.000
So he told me that, you know, I, I cannot allow the bus to be used.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:16.000
And that meant that the students had to march from the campus all the way down, which is the main thoroughfail and where he's rode.

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:25.000
So, downtown to another main thoroughfail to go to the, to the, to the drugstore that they were protesting at.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:34.000
And it was a kind of, interesting kind of day. It looked like a very somber march.

00:20:34.000 --> 00:20:37.000
And the students were single files about seven of them.

00:20:37.000 --> 00:20:43.000
And they had only a Sunday best and they had on trench coats because it was kind of cool.

00:20:43.000 --> 00:20:49.000
And they marched all the way downtown and went down and they were arrested at that point.

00:20:49.000 --> 00:20:55.000
The, the priest from the school.

00:20:55.000 --> 00:20:57.000
We're rolling.

00:20:57.000 --> 00:21:03.000
So there, there was a certain people were arrested. Where were you in all this?

00:21:03.000 --> 00:21:12.000
Well, I was, uh, first, let me just say that because nobody actually knew what the consequences of even unintended consequences were going to be.

00:21:12.000 --> 00:21:22.000
The guys decided not to have any of the young ladies involved because they know that it was going to be some police brutality and arrest and all those kinds of things.

00:21:22.000 --> 00:21:27.000
And they've used to allow any high school students to be involved.

00:21:27.000 --> 00:21:31.000
Now, you could be involved in the planning and strategy and all that kind of thing.

00:21:31.000 --> 00:21:37.000
So I was involved in, in the planning and the strategy and all that, but I couldn't be involved in the demonstrations.

00:21:37.000 --> 00:21:48.000
There were arrested and the, um, the priest from the college actually goes down and, and get, retrieve them and bring them back to the campus.

00:21:48.000 --> 00:21:55.000
I don't think charges will have a, a fix to that because that was never a trial or anything.

00:21:55.000 --> 00:22:08.000
And I stayed actively involved with these students as they, they went to churches and, and other places that were known to be segregated in Denmark.

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:13.000
And we're a few, except into first Baptist church and a couple other churches and that kind of thing.

00:22:13.000 --> 00:22:23.000
So we stayed active and we stayed connected to the other, um, groups that were engaged in protests, uh, doing that particular period of time.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:30.000
And your autobiography, the river of no return, you write that your father was not too excited about your act.

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:34.000
Well, my activities began to accelerate.

00:22:34.000 --> 00:22:39.000
And one of the things that I wanted to do was to put together an organization.

00:22:39.000 --> 00:22:44.000
So, uh, I was thinking about a youth chapter of the NAACP.

00:22:44.000 --> 00:22:49.000
And I began to, uh, organize a youth chapter of the NAACP.

00:22:49.000 --> 00:22:56.000
And once we got it all organized and we got our cards and the college got its official charter.

00:22:56.000 --> 00:23:08.000
Um, I wanted to have a rally that would just simply say to the community that there was a youth chapter of the NAACP in the city of Denmark.

00:23:08.000 --> 00:23:13.000
At that point there was no NAACP chapter.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:24.000
And when I did that, I invited, uh, one of the representatives out of, out of Atlanta, the come and speak for the rally.

00:23:24.000 --> 00:23:29.000
I got to church, Rome, Baptist church and all of that kind of stuff.

00:23:29.000 --> 00:23:35.000
And then, uh, I think it was the day of, of the day before.

00:23:35.000 --> 00:23:45.000
Uh, my father said that, uh, I would have to reframe from being engaged in this activity and I could not go to the meeting.

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:46.000
How did you respond to that?

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:54.000
Oh, I was real upset because I had done a lot of the legwork and pulled people together and gotten people to commit themselves to going in.

00:23:54.000 --> 00:23:58.000
All of a sudden he said that you would not even be there at the program.

00:23:58.000 --> 00:24:06.000
I was, I was really upset and, um, and, and indicated that kind of upset and discuss with him.

00:24:06.000 --> 00:24:23.000
But I did not go. I mean, I stayed, but I figured that it was time for me then to start looking for other places to be because I was, I had been bitten by this bug of, of Emmett Till and movement activities that were going on, et cetera.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:39.000
So, um, I began to, to, to look at the possibilities of going to a, a private school and I wrote Stanton, uh, Staunton Military Academy up in, uh, up in Virginia.

00:24:39.000 --> 00:24:43.000
And, uh, I sent the application in and all that kind of thing.

00:24:43.000 --> 00:24:47.000
And where they had race, I didn't put anything.

00:24:47.000 --> 00:25:01.000
And so they called me and asked me, um, what, what, that, you know, they were looking favorably at me and they said they saw that I did not put in race.

00:25:01.000 --> 00:25:06.000
And they asked me if I was, was, was, was Negro.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:09.000
And I said, yes. And they said, we'll sorry.

00:25:09.000 --> 00:25:11.000
But, uh, we're not going to be able to accept you.

00:25:11.000 --> 00:25:13.000
You thought you'd have a shot there.

00:25:13.000 --> 00:25:22.000
I thought I was going to have a shot somewhere. I was just trying to get to an environment where I could kind of be my own person in regards to the movement.

00:25:22.000 --> 00:25:28.000
And after that went by, I, I feed that I was going to do the rest of my time there.

00:25:28.000 --> 00:25:37.000
And so I really got, uh, more involved with trying to tap in and support other, other movements.

00:25:37.000 --> 00:25:46.000
One of those efforts was that we got the same group of young people that made up the youth in WACP.

00:25:46.000 --> 00:26:00.000
And we went up to Rock Hill when the, um, the Freedom Riders had come through and then you had, uh, protest of that by what was then known as the Rock Hill 9.

00:26:00.000 --> 00:26:03.000
And this was before you were in college.

00:26:03.000 --> 00:26:14.000
Before I was in college here. And when I went up Charles Jones and Diane Nash and, uh, Ruby Dyer's Robinson had gotten arrested.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:27.000
They had come in from, from Atlanta to, uh, protest the rest of the, uh, and so they, that's where the jail no bail kind of, uh, first time he was met these.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:33.000
I didn't meet him. I went up, I went up to meet him and they were in jail.

00:26:33.000 --> 00:26:39.000
And they had a session in which you could actually go out, but we went up early one morning.

00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:47.000
We had the, the principles call, um, the priest call and my mother's car.

00:26:47.000 --> 00:26:52.000
We had three cars and we took three cars full of students from here up there.

00:26:52.000 --> 00:27:10.000
And I think that in that way we stayed connected, but I learned of Charles Jones and I learned of, of, um, Ruby Dyer's and, and Diane and, um, there was another person there and I can't remember who it was.

00:27:10.000 --> 00:27:31.000
I just don't want to say somebody who had went, but there were four, uh, snickers who had come to that area to give that support and they went to jail and they talked about, uh, Ruby Dyer's talked about the fact that there, there was so much, uh, outpouring of support in that community and food.

00:27:31.000 --> 00:27:41.000
And I think she said she gained about 11 pounds in the 30 days that she was out there. But anyhow, that's, that was another link and another connection.

00:27:41.000 --> 00:27:53.000
And then I began to find in the state of South Carolina, there were other, uh, students that were becoming more active, militant, brown, down in Charleston was getting ready.

00:27:53.000 --> 00:28:00.000
And the father was the head of the NAACP. They were getting ready to file a suit to desegate to schools in Charleston.

00:28:00.000 --> 00:28:18.000
And, uh, a, uh, a, uh, uh, uh, a, attorney Matthew J. Perry Jr also was getting ready to file a suit on behalf of, um, of, um, uh, gant, hobby, gant at Clemson.

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:23.000
later the three students at the University of South Carolina.

00:28:23.000 --> 00:28:26.160
So there was a lot of activity beginning to brew,

00:28:26.160 --> 00:28:29.560
and we tried to tap into that to get that kind of support.

00:28:29.560 --> 00:28:32.240
And then we off to Howard.

00:28:32.240 --> 00:28:33.400
Yeah, talk about you.

00:28:33.400 --> 00:28:36.160
A role in Howard in the fall of 62, I think.

00:28:36.160 --> 00:28:36.840
Yes.

00:28:36.840 --> 00:28:39.520
What kind of a school did you, what were you expecting

00:28:39.520 --> 00:28:40.280
and what did you try?

00:28:40.280 --> 00:28:44.080
Well, I expected Howard because it was considered

00:28:44.080 --> 00:28:49.080
one of the larger HBCUs with a lot of history and tradition.

00:28:49.120 --> 00:28:51.240
I expected it to be a hotbed.

00:28:51.240 --> 00:28:52.880
You know, I'd come out of Voorhees

00:28:52.880 --> 00:28:55.560
and there was a lot of activity and action

00:28:55.560 --> 00:28:57.840
and a lot of students involved.

00:28:57.840 --> 00:29:02.840
And you know, we come, I guess,

00:29:05.080 --> 00:29:07.360
Booker T. Washington schools were considered

00:29:07.360 --> 00:29:09.800
to be the kind of blue collar schools,

00:29:09.800 --> 00:29:13.280
you know, the kind of laborers and workers

00:29:13.280 --> 00:29:14.400
and those kind of schools.

00:29:14.400 --> 00:29:19.400
And I didn't know that there was a kind of professional

00:29:21.400 --> 00:29:26.400
white collar kind of bourgeois campus

00:29:26.560 --> 00:29:28.160
like I discovered at Howard.

00:29:28.160 --> 00:29:33.160
And so it was common for us to wear jeans to school.

00:29:35.640 --> 00:29:37.760
And coming out of the South,

00:29:37.760 --> 00:29:41.880
your hair was a little bit longer than the average

00:29:41.880 --> 00:29:46.000
who had the skint down and all that other kind of hairdos.

00:29:47.640 --> 00:29:52.640
And so that was a kind of contentious kind of relationship

00:29:55.120 --> 00:29:58.560
that I have with Howard that people had some difficulty

00:29:58.560 --> 00:30:01.840
with my way in jeans and Howard,

00:30:01.840 --> 00:30:06.440
the young men wore pants, slacks and shirts.

00:30:06.440 --> 00:30:10.200
And it was, if you were really very spiffy

00:30:10.960 --> 00:30:14.680
and upbeat at lunch, you would change your shirt.

00:30:14.680 --> 00:30:17.080
You wouldn't go back to class with the same shirt on.

00:30:17.080 --> 00:30:18.760
So they were striving to become?

00:30:18.760 --> 00:30:22.080
They were striving to become a part of the status quo.

00:30:22.080 --> 00:30:27.080
And we were saying essentially that we need to be

00:30:28.440 --> 00:30:31.120
opening that whole process up.

00:30:31.120 --> 00:30:33.400
We don't need to be trying to be the token.

00:30:33.400 --> 00:30:37.480
And so that's the way I felt that my experience

00:30:37.760 --> 00:30:41.720
would be there, that I would be groomed to be open up.

00:30:41.720 --> 00:30:43.880
Non-dialand action group name.

00:30:43.880 --> 00:30:44.720
Yes.

00:30:46.080 --> 00:30:48.280
Your activities there, what kinds of things

00:30:48.280 --> 00:30:50.400
you're doing, who were you there?

00:30:50.400 --> 00:30:54.080
Well, I was for a long time trying to find that niche.

00:30:54.080 --> 00:30:59.080
And then I found maybe Mike Thelwell,

00:30:59.640 --> 00:31:02.680
some of the others and they, and standing wise

00:31:02.680 --> 00:31:05.920
and they told me about a meeting that they were having.

00:31:05.920 --> 00:31:08.120
And I said, okay, well, I'll come to the meeting

00:31:08.120 --> 00:31:11.680
and went to the meeting and there was a group of maybe

00:31:11.680 --> 00:31:15.880
15 or 20, it grew after I joined.

00:31:15.880 --> 00:31:18.600
And some of the others joined, it was Charlie Cobb

00:31:18.600 --> 00:31:20.160
and a number of other folks.

00:31:20.160 --> 00:31:25.000
Plus there was a, a SNCC office in Washington, DC.

00:31:25.000 --> 00:31:27.120
And it would have, you know,

00:31:27.120 --> 00:31:30.080
I have in Holdon, Olson and some of the other field staff

00:31:30.080 --> 00:31:32.280
would be coming through periodically.

00:31:32.280 --> 00:31:35.400
But what we were committed to was

00:31:35.400 --> 00:31:38.120
learning more about the movement in the South

00:31:38.120 --> 00:31:40.800
and trying to address issues

00:31:40.800 --> 00:31:42.800
that needed to be addressed,

00:31:42.800 --> 00:31:45.840
of communicating information.

00:31:45.840 --> 00:31:50.040
Fun example, the whole issue about protection of voter rights

00:31:50.040 --> 00:31:53.000
and civil rights workers in the South.

00:31:53.000 --> 00:31:55.840
We ended up going to the Justice Department and picketing.

00:31:55.840 --> 00:31:58.320
We ended up at the FBI and picketing.

00:31:58.320 --> 00:32:00.480
We ended up at the White House and picketing.

00:32:00.520 --> 00:32:03.120
That was our job and that was our role.

00:32:03.120 --> 00:32:08.120
But we also had issues that were germane to DC.

00:32:08.400 --> 00:32:11.080
Home rule was one of those issues.

00:32:11.080 --> 00:32:14.680
The buses, I think it was run by a guy by name

00:32:14.680 --> 00:32:16.840
with chalk as I remember it.

00:32:16.840 --> 00:32:19.040
And desegregating of the buses

00:32:19.040 --> 00:32:24.040
and the employment of black drivers and that kind of thing.

00:32:24.600 --> 00:32:28.080
So we tried to mobilize the school

00:32:28.080 --> 00:32:30.360
to respond to those kinds of things

00:32:30.880 --> 00:32:32.880
and one of the things we recognized was that

00:32:32.880 --> 00:32:36.000
you had to be in those critical places

00:32:36.000 --> 00:32:39.800
at the school in order for you to be effective in communicating.

00:32:39.800 --> 00:32:43.520
So we had people who went on the hilltop.

00:32:43.520 --> 00:32:47.480
That was the newspaper, the student newspaper,

00:32:47.480 --> 00:32:51.520
the Lycium program, the Student Government Association

00:32:51.520 --> 00:32:54.680
and many of the organizations we wanted to have people

00:32:54.680 --> 00:32:57.600
in field traded all those things

00:32:57.640 --> 00:33:01.520
and actually began to have that kind of impact

00:33:01.520 --> 00:33:04.880
and we began to try to target those kinds of things.

00:33:04.880 --> 00:33:09.400
On the Lycium program, we started out trying to secure

00:33:09.400 --> 00:33:14.400
the services of biode-rested

00:33:14.600 --> 00:33:16.680
and the administration backed up

00:33:16.680 --> 00:33:19.400
because biode was supposed to be a socialist

00:33:19.400 --> 00:33:22.000
and we kept pushing and we kept pushing

00:33:22.000 --> 00:33:25.320
and we kept pushing and we actually got biode there.

00:33:25.360 --> 00:33:28.160
After these programs, we would have an opportunity

00:33:28.160 --> 00:33:32.760
to have a kind of a one-on-one with whoever that speaker was

00:33:32.760 --> 00:33:35.920
and we had a one-on-one with biode about tactics

00:33:35.920 --> 00:33:38.760
and history and all those other kinds of things.

00:33:38.760 --> 00:33:42.680
We recognized biode as being a good organizer

00:33:42.680 --> 00:33:46.480
and we weren't about to try to take that away from him.

00:33:46.480 --> 00:33:50.720
And so when you get around to the March on Washington

00:33:50.720 --> 00:33:53.560
then biode reached back to get some of us

00:33:53.600 --> 00:33:58.560
and some of the other snickers to work on the March

00:33:58.560 --> 00:34:01.080
under the logistics couple of weeks before the March.

00:34:01.080 --> 00:34:04.760
We were in DC and we had the responsibility

00:34:04.760 --> 00:34:08.240
for all various and so-and-so kinds of logistics

00:34:08.240 --> 00:34:13.240
moving people around, crowd, setting up the designated areas

00:34:14.120 --> 00:34:17.240
for people to arrive and marshaling them

00:34:17.240 --> 00:34:22.240
from the Washington monument down to the Lincoln Memorial.

00:34:22.600 --> 00:34:24.720
Those kinds of things, even making the signs

00:34:24.720 --> 00:34:26.200
and making the sandwiches.

00:34:26.200 --> 00:34:29.440
So we had those assignments

00:34:29.440 --> 00:34:32.200
and that was a unique opportunity and experience.

00:34:32.200 --> 00:34:35.600
But before we even got there, we also decided

00:34:35.600 --> 00:34:37.960
that once we were successful with biode

00:34:37.960 --> 00:34:39.960
that we would go for Malcolm

00:34:39.960 --> 00:34:43.640
and we were able to push the school on the Malcolm issue

00:34:43.640 --> 00:34:47.720
and Malcolm actually came to the campus.

00:34:47.720 --> 00:34:49.240
He had a wonderful presentation

00:34:49.240 --> 00:34:51.840
though Auditorium was absolutely full

00:34:51.880 --> 00:34:55.080
and after it was over we had an opportunity to talk

00:34:55.080 --> 00:34:57.880
with Malcolm and-

00:34:57.880 --> 00:35:00.760
The conversation was interesting because

00:35:00.760 --> 00:35:04.800
that phase was like many kinds of things to say about

00:35:04.800 --> 00:35:05.640
so we're right to move.

00:35:05.640 --> 00:35:06.800
That's absolutely correct.

00:35:06.800 --> 00:35:09.240
So you know we had that kind of debate

00:35:09.240 --> 00:35:12.960
and we pushed all those kinds of issues.

00:35:12.960 --> 00:35:17.960
And I think that one of the things that Malcolm used

00:35:17.960 --> 00:35:19.480
to refer to-

00:35:19.480 --> 00:35:23.320
I said the students of the movement,

00:35:23.320 --> 00:35:25.440
that's how he referred to that whole group.

00:35:25.440 --> 00:35:28.840
And we used to run into each other

00:35:28.840 --> 00:35:30.840
and I'm talking about with the Snickers

00:35:30.840 --> 00:35:33.520
in Washington frequently

00:35:33.520 --> 00:35:36.920
and we would always stop and have that discussion

00:35:36.920 --> 00:35:38.960
about what was going on.

00:35:38.960 --> 00:35:41.960
Matter of fact when the March on Washington was going on,

00:35:42.960 --> 00:35:46.200
Malcolm was in Washington and he called it

00:35:46.200 --> 00:35:47.680
the Forest on Washington

00:35:47.680 --> 00:35:51.200
and he talked about the big six and all that other kind of stuff.

00:35:51.200 --> 00:35:53.440
For the only time he met King and Person I think was-

00:35:53.440 --> 00:35:55.920
Yes, at the airport.

00:35:55.920 --> 00:35:56.920
Yeah.

00:35:56.920 --> 00:35:59.160
And they just kind of ran in each other

00:35:59.160 --> 00:36:00.760
and wasn't playing anything.

00:36:01.760 --> 00:36:05.360
The March, Biod Rustin was the principal organizer

00:36:05.360 --> 00:36:07.880
and it was to be a protest march

00:36:07.880 --> 00:36:09.640
but it really turned out that way.

00:36:09.640 --> 00:36:10.440
No, it-

00:36:10.440 --> 00:36:12.120
Talk about your feelings about.

00:36:12.120 --> 00:36:15.240
You've done all this work, you've done all this organization,

00:36:15.240 --> 00:36:18.400
you've got hundreds of thousands of people there.

00:36:18.400 --> 00:36:21.200
Well, I think that for many of us,

00:36:21.200 --> 00:36:23.160
even including the Snickers,

00:36:24.800 --> 00:36:29.280
we were on the edge and it was a fledging kind of movement

00:36:29.280 --> 00:36:31.040
of Snickers at this point.

00:36:31.040 --> 00:36:35.640
We're still in an infestage even though we have been in Albany

00:36:35.640 --> 00:36:37.920
and we've been in Danville

00:36:37.920 --> 00:36:40.040
and we've been in a lot of other areas.

00:36:41.200 --> 00:36:43.480
We were growing

00:36:43.520 --> 00:36:46.680
and you had a small number of people

00:36:46.680 --> 00:36:48.720
that involved in Snickers at that point

00:36:48.720 --> 00:36:51.400
on a regular basis, on a full-time basis.

00:36:51.400 --> 00:36:54.040
So we were using a lot of students

00:36:54.040 --> 00:36:56.600
who would come doing the summer,

00:36:56.600 --> 00:37:00.080
come doing a spring break or whenever it was.

00:37:00.080 --> 00:37:02.720
And so we hadn't really gotten to the point

00:37:02.720 --> 00:37:07.240
where we were talking about full-time organizers

00:37:07.240 --> 00:37:09.640
working in any particular area.

00:37:09.640 --> 00:37:14.640
So the March on Washington was one of those learning periods.

00:37:15.760 --> 00:37:18.080
John Lewis speech, for an example.

00:37:18.080 --> 00:37:19.880
The changing of that speech.

00:37:19.880 --> 00:37:22.440
That was what was so controversial about it

00:37:22.440 --> 00:37:23.720
that it needed to be changed.

00:37:23.720 --> 00:37:26.960
Well, there was some objection,

00:37:26.960 --> 00:37:30.720
one of the cardinals, Patrick O'Boyle, I think it's his name.

00:37:30.720 --> 00:37:33.920
He was concerned that John used a language

00:37:33.920 --> 00:37:38.280
that we would go through the South like Sherman

00:37:38.280 --> 00:37:43.280
and burning the vestiges of segregation to the ground.

00:37:44.640 --> 00:37:45.640
Wonderful metaphor.

00:37:45.640 --> 00:37:49.160
I understand, but they said to Vowlin,

00:37:49.160 --> 00:37:51.960
to you know, and this go create more.

00:37:51.960 --> 00:37:55.280
And I think, you know, just Southern was just subjected

00:37:55.280 --> 00:37:57.040
to that kind of terminology.

00:37:58.000 --> 00:38:00.280
But the critical piece was that

00:38:02.360 --> 00:38:06.920
A. Philip Randolph actually came to the Snickers

00:38:06.920 --> 00:38:10.760
and said, you know, I've been working on this ever since 1940.

00:38:10.760 --> 00:38:15.760
This is, and I'm close to having a dream fulfill.

00:38:16.880 --> 00:38:18.280
Can you help me with this?

00:38:18.280 --> 00:38:19.840
And I would really, really appreciate it

00:38:19.840 --> 00:38:21.240
if you would make that.

00:38:21.240 --> 00:38:26.240
And I think out of our, I guess,

00:38:27.160 --> 00:38:32.160
commitment to a kind of person whose show as we were standing,

00:38:32.400 --> 00:38:37.160
we said that we would actually make those changes

00:38:37.920 --> 00:38:40.160
and not feel any guilt about that.

00:38:40.160 --> 00:38:45.080
But I think that was also a critical point for the organization

00:38:45.080 --> 00:38:48.840
because then we had to come to the conclusion

00:38:48.840 --> 00:38:51.720
that we had to, if we had voice,

00:38:51.720 --> 00:38:53.800
we had to be able to control it

00:38:53.800 --> 00:38:55.920
and we had to be able to live up to it.

00:38:55.920 --> 00:39:00.200
So after that, you didn't have people kind of coming in

00:39:00.200 --> 00:39:02.320
saying, this is what you need,

00:39:02.320 --> 00:39:05.280
and that's what you need and what you change your position

00:39:05.280 --> 00:39:07.400
for the sake of me, anything else.

00:39:08.960 --> 00:39:12.200
So we were very idealistic.

00:39:12.200 --> 00:39:16.000
And so we thought that the March would have the kind of impact

00:39:16.000 --> 00:39:17.320
that it may have.

00:39:17.320 --> 00:39:20.640
And that is getting the message out about civil rights,

00:39:20.640 --> 00:39:25.640
education, you know, health, welfare, those employment,

00:39:26.200 --> 00:39:28.040
those kinds of things.

00:39:28.080 --> 00:39:33.080
And we also saw that as the first real time

00:39:33.240 --> 00:39:35.840
that on a national scale, you had the coalition

00:39:35.840 --> 00:39:40.840
of civil rights, church, and kind of democratic liberalism

00:39:42.560 --> 00:39:46.160
that would kind of come together for that particular thing.

00:39:47.680 --> 00:39:50.600
And so there was a euphoria, I think, for many of us,

00:39:50.600 --> 00:39:53.520
we were tired, exhausted, we worked very hard,

00:39:53.520 --> 00:39:55.960
and there was a kind of euphoria.

00:39:55.960 --> 00:40:00.280
And we were in the kind of ideal world in terms of now.

00:40:01.040 --> 00:40:06.040
After Montgomery and after all the things

00:40:07.800 --> 00:40:11.800
that had gone on, including mega-evils

00:40:13.720 --> 00:40:17.320
and the students in Birmingham and the horses

00:40:17.320 --> 00:40:21.520
and the dogs and the firehoses and all that kind of stuff,

00:40:21.520 --> 00:40:26.520
that we had actually found a way to bring some kind of,

00:40:27.640 --> 00:40:32.440
not closure, but bring some consolidation of all those things.

00:40:32.440 --> 00:40:37.440
And the 16th Street Baptist Church Bombing kind of destroyed

00:40:39.440 --> 00:40:40.200
all of that.

00:40:40.200 --> 00:40:42.520
And so you're back to the real world.

00:40:42.520 --> 00:40:46.120
And I think that at that point, you know,

00:40:46.120 --> 00:40:49.120
eyes began to open up and we knew that we had to get back

00:40:49.120 --> 00:40:50.640
to real business.

00:40:50.640 --> 00:40:55.640
But we also, for many of us of the Emmett Teal generation,

00:40:57.600 --> 00:41:01.280
recognize that we probably couldn't do this as part time.

00:41:01.280 --> 00:41:03.360
And so we had to make some serious decisions

00:41:03.360 --> 00:41:07.560
about going full time with civil rights

00:41:07.560 --> 00:41:11.320
or leaving that to who could go full time

00:41:11.320 --> 00:41:14.040
and get busy about our academics.

00:41:14.040 --> 00:41:15.040
You couldn't do both.

00:41:15.040 --> 00:41:17.080
So what did you drop out of that?

00:41:17.080 --> 00:41:19.080
I was, I was, I was, I was, I was, I was, I was,

00:41:19.080 --> 00:41:20.080
okay, we're back.

00:41:22.280 --> 00:41:23.120
Okay.

00:41:24.720 --> 00:41:29.400
So you were realizing that you were going to have to be full time.

00:41:29.400 --> 00:41:31.560
When did you leave Howard?

00:41:32.560 --> 00:41:35.400
Well, yeah, yeah.

00:41:35.400 --> 00:41:40.400
We were assigned by Bob Moses,

00:41:41.280 --> 00:41:46.280
we being nagged to be responsible for generating

00:41:47.280 --> 00:41:51.280
and getting volunteers for the summer of 64.

00:41:53.360 --> 00:41:57.200
And we also understood that we would be committing ourselves.

00:41:57.200 --> 00:42:01.920
So all of Nag, probably 90% of Nag would go down.

00:42:01.920 --> 00:42:05.160
But we had to recruit from the University of Maryland,

00:42:05.160 --> 00:42:07.040
Morgan State, George Washington,

00:42:07.040 --> 00:42:09.160
Joyce, American University.

00:42:09.160 --> 00:42:13.040
Those schools in that Maryland DC cluster

00:42:13.040 --> 00:42:15.880
would be the schools that we would actually recruit from.

00:42:15.880 --> 00:42:18.800
And one of the unique parts about the recruitment

00:42:18.800 --> 00:42:22.720
that we were doing is that most of the students

00:42:22.720 --> 00:42:25.680
that we were recruiting were going to be African-Americans.

00:42:25.680 --> 00:42:28.240
There were whites in there that actually went down

00:42:28.240 --> 00:42:29.400
from that area.

00:42:29.400 --> 00:42:31.520
But we would have the largest contingency

00:42:31.520 --> 00:42:36.080
of African-American volunteers that we go down.

00:42:36.080 --> 00:42:40.800
And so we kind of leveraged that to get

00:42:40.800 --> 00:42:44.120
into the second congressional district of Mississippi,

00:42:44.120 --> 00:42:45.880
which was the plantation area.

00:42:45.880 --> 00:42:50.880
And that was the black belt of Mississippi.

00:42:52.880 --> 00:42:56.040
And we felt like if we could get into those areas,

00:42:56.040 --> 00:43:00.760
we could be much more effective in trying to get down in

00:43:00.760 --> 00:43:04.120
and get these communities to kind of empower them

00:43:04.120 --> 00:43:08.920
to organize and to put us out of our job,

00:43:08.920 --> 00:43:10.240
put us out of work.

00:43:10.240 --> 00:43:15.480
But I probably knew as soon as I made the commitment

00:43:15.480 --> 00:43:18.960
to go to Mississippi, that would probably be it.

00:43:18.960 --> 00:43:23.760
So I finished the semester at how it,

00:43:23.760 --> 00:43:26.800
but most of that time, at the end of that semester,

00:43:26.800 --> 00:43:29.280
I was in Cambridge, Maryland.

00:43:29.280 --> 00:43:31.160
Talk about the Cambridge movement.

00:43:31.160 --> 00:43:33.440
It became very violent with the lower

00:43:33.440 --> 00:43:36.480
enrichances of the cleaning it.

00:43:36.480 --> 00:43:38.800
Well, Cambridge, when we first went over,

00:43:38.800 --> 00:43:42.880
was basically trying to organize the community

00:43:42.880 --> 00:43:47.800
to have protests in that community.

00:43:47.800 --> 00:43:52.360
And each time the protests ended up

00:43:52.360 --> 00:43:54.280
in some kind of violent scuffle.

00:43:54.280 --> 00:43:59.440
And at a point there, you had martial law in Cambridge.

00:43:59.440 --> 00:44:06.480
And then the opposition in Cambridge invited in George C. Wallace.

00:44:06.480 --> 00:44:07.560
We were in.

00:44:07.560 --> 00:44:09.920
I was in Cambridge at that particular time.

00:44:09.920 --> 00:44:14.200
And the National Guard was in charge,

00:44:14.200 --> 00:44:18.680
eye along with Stokeley and Stanley Wise.

00:44:18.680 --> 00:44:23.720
And Gloria were arrested and kept in a National Guard

00:44:23.720 --> 00:44:25.000
armory overnight.

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:28.240
We were freed the next day.

00:44:28.240 --> 00:44:32.680
But at that point, the Cambridge movement itself,

00:44:32.680 --> 00:44:36.040
there were elements in it that wanted to strike out.

00:44:36.040 --> 00:44:40.600
And there was efforts made to kind of contain that.

00:44:40.600 --> 00:44:43.360
But Gloria was a little bit more radical

00:44:43.360 --> 00:44:46.800
than most people had expected.

00:44:46.800 --> 00:44:52.280
And she was one of those, first, she was a how it graduates.

00:44:52.280 --> 00:44:56.360
So that was one of the connections that she had with Nag.

00:44:56.360 --> 00:45:00.320
And so she was able to get additional nag, John Patisse,

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:02.160
from how it actually goes up.

00:45:02.160 --> 00:45:07.040
And Reginald Robinson is in Cambridge, Maryland.

00:45:07.040 --> 00:45:11.520
And then it got to the point where Robert F. Kennedy

00:45:11.520 --> 00:45:16.720
wanted to intercede and see if he could find a remedy for Cambridge.

00:45:16.720 --> 00:45:18.800
And so I think what he ended up doing

00:45:18.800 --> 00:45:20.440
was extending the martial law.

00:45:20.440 --> 00:45:24.640
It stayed in place for a little over a year in Cambridge.

00:45:24.640 --> 00:45:26.640
And they began to have some dialogues

00:45:26.640 --> 00:45:30.600
between the community about desegregation of Cambridge.

00:45:30.600 --> 00:45:37.800
So doing that that spring is when Wallace came to Cambridge.

00:45:37.800 --> 00:45:42.680
And the National Guard had this tear gas.

00:45:42.680 --> 00:45:45.680
I don't know if they had some kind of combination mixture

00:45:45.680 --> 00:45:50.040
of tear gas and some elements of chemicals

00:45:50.040 --> 00:45:53.920
that actually made you nauseate it.

00:45:53.920 --> 00:45:57.360
And so we had all these things going on at the same time.

00:45:57.360 --> 00:46:01.480
Cliff Vaughs's one of the photographers for SNCC

00:46:01.480 --> 00:46:04.720
was actually arrested.

00:46:04.720 --> 00:46:09.400
And some way he was hit with a bayonet

00:46:09.400 --> 00:46:10.800
through the calf of his legs.

00:46:10.800 --> 00:46:16.560
So it was a very scary night when the tear gas was used.

00:46:16.560 --> 00:46:19.680
You had these young national guards men out there.

00:46:19.680 --> 00:46:23.480
And they just kind of the police brutality kind of thing

00:46:23.480 --> 00:46:24.920
and throwing everybody in the truck.

00:46:24.920 --> 00:46:26.680
And we were all arrested.

00:46:26.680 --> 00:46:27.560
And that kind of thing.

00:46:27.560 --> 00:46:31.600
And we ended up going to the stock A, as I said, and were released.

00:46:31.600 --> 00:46:34.560
The general in charge of that operation,

00:46:34.560 --> 00:46:36.680
and I think it was named was Gelson.

00:46:36.680 --> 00:46:40.120
And he was trying to negotiate this stuff.

00:46:40.120 --> 00:46:41.680
And he's an army general.

00:46:41.680 --> 00:46:44.000
He's trying to be a police chief.

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:47.160
And so it got real confusing and complex.

00:46:47.160 --> 00:46:51.520
At that point, that's what I think Robert F. Kennedy

00:46:51.520 --> 00:46:52.640
interceded.

00:46:52.640 --> 00:46:54.720
Now what we were trying to do is we were trying

00:46:54.720 --> 00:47:01.040
to have a march from the black section of Cambridge

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:05.200
over to the, I think he was at the National Guard Army,

00:47:05.200 --> 00:47:09.240
where George C. Wallace was speaking.

00:47:09.240 --> 00:47:12.320
And that's how this whole thing kind of got out of whack

00:47:12.320 --> 00:47:13.520
over there.

00:47:13.520 --> 00:47:18.960
I left Cambridge, went back to how it

00:47:18.960 --> 00:47:22.680
tried to finish up my semester and prepare

00:47:22.680 --> 00:47:24.720
to go to Mississippi for that summer.

00:47:24.720 --> 00:47:28.560
Because we were not only trying to recruit

00:47:28.560 --> 00:47:30.640
student activists to go to Mississippi,

00:47:30.640 --> 00:47:35.400
we also trying to get automobiles and other resources

00:47:35.400 --> 00:47:37.040
that we would take to Mississippi.

00:47:37.040 --> 00:47:42.280
So I think we ended up having two or three calls donated,

00:47:42.280 --> 00:47:44.200
all of which we drove out.

00:47:44.200 --> 00:47:49.840
And then in June, we drove out to Ohio for the orientation.

00:47:49.840 --> 00:47:55.060
Freedom Summer was a project in Smith and Copa

00:47:55.060 --> 00:47:58.960
Council of Federal, right in organizations initiated,

00:47:58.960 --> 00:48:01.240
in part because the federal government

00:48:01.240 --> 00:48:05.040
was not paying attention to all the abuses in Mississippi.

00:48:05.040 --> 00:48:09.160
And the idea was that by inviting upwards

00:48:09.160 --> 00:48:12.640
of the thousand volunteers to spend their summers in Mississippi,

00:48:12.640 --> 00:48:15.880
it would shine the spotlight on the state

00:48:15.880 --> 00:48:18.760
and force the federal government to do something,

00:48:18.760 --> 00:48:21.360
among other things.

00:48:21.360 --> 00:48:25.480
Freedom Summer became international news

00:48:25.480 --> 00:48:30.000
when three civil rights workers Andrew Goodman, Michael

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:36.840
Michael "Mickey" Schwerner and James Chaney were abducted and killed by the clan.

00:48:36.840 --> 00:48:41.720
What most people think is then the FBI came in,

00:48:41.720 --> 00:48:44.080
and all you hear about is the FBI.

00:48:44.080 --> 00:48:47.880
But it was very interesting that you and other people

00:48:47.880 --> 00:48:52.320
who had just come to Mississippi were out looking for them.

00:48:52.320 --> 00:48:53.240
They had disappeared.

00:48:53.240 --> 00:48:55.640
The bodies would not be found for months.

00:48:55.640 --> 00:48:59.200
Talk about going into Mississippi and who was there

00:48:59.200 --> 00:49:01.400
and how you went about looking.

00:49:01.400 --> 00:49:08.080
Well, when we get out to Ohio, Miami,

00:49:08.080 --> 00:49:14.160
University at Ohio, at the Anno-Hail,

00:49:14.160 --> 00:49:19.240
we had the orientation session set up.

00:49:19.240 --> 00:49:25.480
And we were going through the orientation sessions.

00:49:25.480 --> 00:49:30.920
And then we got some information that a church had been

00:49:30.920 --> 00:49:34.560
burned to the ground in Philadelphia.

00:49:34.560 --> 00:49:42.160
And so Michael Michael "Mickey" Schwerner and Michael Mickey Michael "Mickey" Schwerner

00:49:42.160 --> 00:49:48.760
and Chaney and they had to pick someone a volunteer to go along with them.

00:49:48.760 --> 00:49:51.360
And they wanted to pick a volunteer to go along with them.

00:49:51.360 --> 00:49:57.920
And so they got Goodman as a volunteer who volunteered to go.

00:49:57.920 --> 00:50:01.960
And they were going to go back and investigate the church burning.

00:50:01.960 --> 00:50:03.120
And so they left.

00:50:03.120 --> 00:50:05.680
And we actually saw him off.

00:50:05.680 --> 00:50:09.680
And they were gone and they went back to Meridian.

00:50:09.680 --> 00:50:10.520
They checked in.

00:50:10.520 --> 00:50:14.400
They went straight from Meridian, all to Philadelphia.

00:50:14.400 --> 00:50:17.000
And they didn't return to Philadelphia.

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:21.240
So we got in a lurch that they were missing.

00:50:21.240 --> 00:50:26.600
And so we gave it about maybe 12 or 24 hours.

00:50:26.600 --> 00:50:31.200
And then that's when I think many of us

00:50:31.200 --> 00:50:35.560
knew that they didn't respond to any of the security messages and all.

00:50:35.560 --> 00:50:43.040
That's something deadly probably had happened to them.

00:50:43.040 --> 00:50:49.200
Bob Assemble, Bob Moses Assemble, all of the folk there.

00:50:49.200 --> 00:50:57.720
And he said, I have you here because I want to let you know the three of our volunteers

00:50:57.720 --> 00:51:03.960
who were here yesterday have been missing.

00:51:03.960 --> 00:51:12.560
And that he had concluded as many of the other seasoned veterans that they were dead.

00:51:12.560 --> 00:51:19.840
And that many people sitting in the room had a choice, a decision to make.

00:51:19.840 --> 00:51:24.240
And that is whether or not they still wanted to go to Mississippi,

00:51:24.240 --> 00:51:31.560
in spite of the fact that there are three people who were like you that already did.

00:51:31.560 --> 00:51:38.120
And at that point, he said that he was still going.

00:51:38.120 --> 00:51:40.120
And he hoped that everybody else would go.

00:51:40.120 --> 00:51:42.720
And at that point, there was a real quiet in the room.

00:51:42.720 --> 00:51:50.440
And I think that Jean Wheeler actually gets up and says,

00:51:50.440 --> 00:51:52.360
starts singing a song.

00:51:52.360 --> 00:51:54.560
And everybody kind of march out.

00:51:54.560 --> 00:52:00.280
Well, when everybody marches out, a collective of us get together with Bob.

00:52:00.280 --> 00:52:03.440
And we say that we are going to go in the Philadelphia.

00:52:03.440 --> 00:52:06.840
And we can see what may have happened.

00:52:06.840 --> 00:52:14.200
And so that consisted of, I think it was Ralph Ralph Featherstone and Dona Richards,

00:52:14.200 --> 00:52:23.400
Bob Moses' wife at that time, Gwen Robinson, I think was her name.

00:52:23.400 --> 00:52:28.440
Stokely Carmichael, Charlie Cobb.

00:52:28.440 --> 00:52:32.160
I think it was Ralph Ralph Featherstone and myself.

00:52:32.160 --> 00:52:34.760
We got in full different cars.

00:52:34.760 --> 00:52:38.440
And we said that we would end a estate from full different directions.

00:52:38.440 --> 00:52:43.360
Stokely Carmichael and Charlie, when one guy came in through Arkansas,

00:52:43.360 --> 00:52:47.800
there was another group that came in through Alabama.

00:52:47.800 --> 00:52:51.600
We came in through Northern Mississippi, down the Mississippi.

00:52:51.600 --> 00:52:53.760
Trace, I think that's what it's called.

00:52:53.760 --> 00:52:56.600
And there was another group that came in through Memphis.

00:52:56.600 --> 00:52:59.040
And then we would all meet in Meridian.

00:52:59.040 --> 00:53:02.280
And once we got in Meridian, we'd get together.

00:53:02.280 --> 00:53:08.160
And there would be some farmers who would go out during the day

00:53:08.160 --> 00:53:13.160
to see if they could find places that bodies would be hidden.

00:53:13.160 --> 00:53:16.120
All where hostages might have been hill.

00:53:16.120 --> 00:53:16.800
And they would-

00:53:16.800 --> 00:53:18.560
Feel that about some hope, did you?

00:53:18.560 --> 00:53:21.760
Well, you always have that in the back of your mind.

00:53:21.840 --> 00:53:27.000
But in reality, we were thinking about bodies

00:53:27.000 --> 00:53:30.200
that we may find more than we were hostages.

00:53:30.200 --> 00:53:41.680
And so we all left Meridian and drove up the Philadelphia at night.

00:53:41.680 --> 00:53:51.680
And during the day, we would be up in the loft of the barn.

00:53:52.200 --> 00:53:57.440
And at night, somebody would come by in a truck

00:53:57.440 --> 00:54:01.520
and it'd take us out and it'd give us a map.

00:54:01.520 --> 00:54:06.080
And we'd go out into the valleys and into old houses

00:54:06.080 --> 00:54:10.000
and all that kind of stuff and see if there was any signs

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:13.160
that hostages were held there, any of that kind of thing.

00:54:13.160 --> 00:54:14.440
We had no lights.

00:54:14.440 --> 00:54:20.960
We couldn't wear but belts because the buckles were glare

00:54:21.000 --> 00:54:25.120
and there were fire towers all over across the south.

00:54:25.120 --> 00:54:29.000
That was one of the safety things that was set up

00:54:29.000 --> 00:54:33.360
so that people go up tall and they could look out over the flat land

00:54:33.360 --> 00:54:35.560
and they could see where there was any smoke or fire

00:54:35.560 --> 00:54:37.480
and they could get to it quickly.

00:54:37.480 --> 00:54:41.920
So we had to be very concerned about those kinds of things.

00:54:41.920 --> 00:54:45.920
And after a certain period of time, we would come back

00:54:45.920 --> 00:54:49.000
maybe three hours, something like that.

00:54:49.040 --> 00:54:51.000
They would come back and pick us up.

00:54:51.000 --> 00:54:54.840
We'd go back to the house and we'd sleep until

00:54:54.840 --> 00:54:57.080
and kind of stir around but we couldn't

00:54:57.080 --> 00:54:58.600
that people know that we were there.

00:54:58.600 --> 00:55:00.920
How many nights were you doing there?

00:55:00.920 --> 00:55:05.920
We did that for, I think it was two nights we were out there.

00:55:07.440 --> 00:55:10.040
And then we had a discussion.

00:55:10.040 --> 00:55:11.920
We used to have discussions all the time

00:55:11.920 --> 00:55:15.720
about what we were doing and our commitment to the movement

00:55:16.000 --> 00:55:23.000
and our friends and how we felt like they were really a part of us.

00:55:26.440 --> 00:55:28.480
Kind of comrades in arms.

00:55:31.320 --> 00:55:36.320
And so we began to feel as if we were being compromised

00:55:36.920 --> 00:55:39.320
in terms of our being out there.

00:55:39.320 --> 00:55:41.760
And we didn't want to have the pressure come on,

00:55:41.760 --> 00:55:46.480
the farmers who were going out looking and transporting us

00:55:46.480 --> 00:55:48.840
and the people at where we were staying.

00:55:48.840 --> 00:55:51.640
So we pulled a plug on it after the second night

00:55:51.640 --> 00:55:55.760
and said we were going back to Meridian.

00:55:55.760 --> 00:55:57.240
And then we would all be dispersed

00:55:57.240 --> 00:56:00.920
to our respected project areas.

00:56:00.920 --> 00:56:03.960
And I fell the stone and I went to Holly Springs.

00:56:03.960 --> 00:56:05.440
So you tell us about Holly Springs.

00:56:05.440 --> 00:56:07.160
What kind of a place was it?

00:56:07.160 --> 00:56:08.440
What did you find there?

00:56:08.440 --> 00:56:10.880
Holly Springs was a community

00:56:11.160 --> 00:56:14.280
in which there were two colleges, two HBCUs.

00:56:14.280 --> 00:56:18.720
One was in decline and the other one is still very vibrant

00:56:18.720 --> 00:56:20.720
and still there now.

00:56:20.720 --> 00:56:25.720
We found a community that had a lot of hope in that community.

00:56:28.120 --> 00:56:31.840
You found that among many of the people who were there.

00:56:31.840 --> 00:56:34.680
There had been some other folk in Holly Springs

00:56:34.680 --> 00:56:35.960
before we got there.

00:56:36.640 --> 00:56:41.160
I think what's his name?

00:56:43.160 --> 00:56:46.160
Leslie McLemore actually graduated from Rust.

00:56:46.160 --> 00:56:48.680
Graduated from Rust, yeah.

00:56:48.680 --> 00:56:51.840
And so there had been some other organizers

00:56:51.840 --> 00:56:55.360
in Holly Springs before we actually got there.

00:56:55.360 --> 00:57:00.000
But because we had the largest project

00:57:00.000 --> 00:57:03.000
and I'm talking about, we took in,

00:57:03.000 --> 00:57:04.960
I think it was five or six counties,

00:57:04.960 --> 00:57:08.000
including Oxford, which was Fayette County

00:57:08.000 --> 00:57:12.560
and Marshall County and many of the other counties

00:57:12.560 --> 00:57:15.240
in Union County in that area.

00:57:15.240 --> 00:57:18.840
That we probably had one of the larger staffs there.

00:57:18.840 --> 00:57:20.840
And it must have been about 12 or 13.

00:57:20.840 --> 00:57:23.280
We had three master school teachers

00:57:23.280 --> 00:57:26.680
out of Boston.

00:57:27.800 --> 00:57:28.960
We had a nurse.

00:57:29.960 --> 00:57:33.360
So we could do clinical work and prevention.

00:57:33.360 --> 00:57:37.320
We could actually go out and have her examined people sometimes

00:57:37.320 --> 00:57:40.840
who may not have been able to access a doctor

00:57:40.840 --> 00:57:42.280
and that kind of thing.

00:57:42.280 --> 00:57:44.920
And we were able to establish a freedom school.

00:57:44.920 --> 00:57:47.680
We operated a community center

00:57:47.680 --> 00:57:50.480
and had activities in for the young people.

00:57:50.480 --> 00:57:56.480
And we actually solicited the largest number of application

00:57:56.800 --> 00:57:59.440
for the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party.

00:57:59.440 --> 00:58:03.680
And we also represented the, in larger proportion

00:58:03.680 --> 00:58:05.520
because we had more delegates

00:58:05.520 --> 00:58:09.040
that went to the state convention and later

00:58:09.040 --> 00:58:11.520
to Atlantic City.

00:58:11.520 --> 00:58:16.520
But that was what the project was like.

00:58:17.520 --> 00:58:21.440
We had an editor from the Cremson,

00:58:22.640 --> 00:58:25.640
who Peter, yes.

00:58:25.640 --> 00:58:29.280
Who was Peter Cummings, I think, was his name.

00:58:29.280 --> 00:58:33.960
And we had a little news letter that we put together.

00:58:33.960 --> 00:58:38.000
We kept meticulous records of our work there

00:58:38.000 --> 00:58:40.360
in out of Holly Springs.

00:58:40.360 --> 00:58:41.920
What was the project director?

00:58:41.920 --> 00:58:45.800
Project director was started out being Ivanhoe Donaldson.

00:58:45.800 --> 00:58:50.800
I took over as project director and was a official project director.

00:58:50.800 --> 00:58:52.280
I was in the fall.

00:58:52.280 --> 00:58:53.760
From you.

00:58:53.760 --> 00:58:54.960
Yeah.

00:58:55.400 --> 00:58:57.680
Ivanhoe Donaldson left after the summer.

00:58:57.680 --> 00:59:01.560
And so I took over after the summer and was project director.

00:59:01.560 --> 00:59:03.680
What sort of reaction did you get

00:59:03.680 --> 00:59:08.000
for the white community for this invasion of all these outside edges?

00:59:08.000 --> 00:59:10.040
Well, Holly Springs was in the north

00:59:10.040 --> 00:59:12.280
and it was more moderate in Holly Springs

00:59:12.280 --> 00:59:13.640
that it was in other places.

00:59:13.640 --> 00:59:14.520
No, in Delphis.

00:59:14.520 --> 00:59:15.640
It was not a Delta.

00:59:15.640 --> 00:59:17.440
It was a certain one in Southwest.

00:59:17.440 --> 00:59:23.120
Southwest is just clandestine groups and shootings

00:59:23.120 --> 00:59:28.040
and arbitrary killings and that kind of thing were common.

00:59:28.040 --> 00:59:32.000
We did have fire bombings and school burnings

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:34.480
and church burnings and all that kind of thing.

00:59:34.480 --> 00:59:39.680
But generally not the kind of individual people

00:59:39.680 --> 00:59:43.680
getting killed at night, lynched in those kinds of things.

00:59:43.680 --> 00:59:46.040
Those things did not happen.

00:59:46.040 --> 00:59:49.880
We did have freedom days in which we actually took people down

00:59:49.880 --> 00:59:52.560
and their names ended up in the newspaper.

00:59:52.560 --> 00:59:54.800
And they probably lost their registered vote.

00:59:54.800 --> 00:59:55.760
Registered vote.

00:59:55.760 --> 00:59:57.880
And we went along without people though.

00:59:57.880 --> 01:00:02.480
Every time they went down to make sure the things were handled very well.

01:00:02.480 --> 01:00:04.840
You want to get registered that summer?

01:00:04.840 --> 01:00:07.640
We had a couple of people that got registered, not very many.

01:00:07.640 --> 01:00:10.440
It's just one go work, one go happen.

01:00:10.440 --> 01:00:15.160
But we did have a number of freedom days

01:00:15.160 --> 01:00:17.320
in which people were actually taken down.

01:00:17.320 --> 01:00:20.520
They just didn't register them.

01:00:20.600 --> 01:00:28.120
But we had a tremendous success in getting young people involved

01:00:28.120 --> 01:00:30.200
and engaged.

01:00:30.200 --> 01:00:36.680
We had a number of students that we sent off to college

01:00:36.680 --> 01:00:40.280
at the end of 1965.

01:00:40.280 --> 01:00:44.680
We had colleges that were willing to accept students

01:00:44.680 --> 01:00:48.480
if we refer to them to them.

01:00:48.480 --> 01:00:52.720
Roy DeBerry was one of those students

01:00:52.720 --> 01:00:57.120
who ended up being a council member down in Jackson.

01:00:57.120 --> 01:00:58.280
Fall on through the time.

01:00:58.280 --> 01:01:00.760
He was a young kid when we came along.

01:01:00.760 --> 01:01:05.720
And we kept providing the kind of nurturing and education

01:01:05.720 --> 01:01:08.000
that we thought he needed.

01:01:08.000 --> 01:01:11.080
And he turned out to be quite a success.

01:01:11.080 --> 01:01:17.000
We had a local project director shortly after I left.

01:01:17.000 --> 01:01:23.800
And that was Rita and her husband.

01:01:23.800 --> 01:01:26.760
And in Holly Springs, there were locals.

01:01:26.760 --> 01:01:28.640
They started out when we started out

01:01:28.640 --> 01:01:30.440
at the beginning of the summer.

01:01:30.440 --> 01:01:36.280
And Rita became an excellent organizer and community leader.

01:01:36.280 --> 01:01:37.240
She died.

01:01:37.240 --> 01:01:40.520
And her husband took over for a couple of minutes

01:01:40.520 --> 01:01:44.160
and stayed around for a period of time.

01:01:44.160 --> 01:01:47.200
We saw our job as going into communities

01:01:47.200 --> 01:01:49.760
and actually organizing those communities

01:01:49.760 --> 01:01:55.920
so that the leadership for giving direction to and organizing

01:01:55.920 --> 01:01:57.720
would be tearing over to the local people.

01:01:57.720 --> 01:02:00.240
We were trying to work our way out of a job.

01:02:00.240 --> 01:02:03.960
So I never felt bad about leaving when I did,

01:02:03.960 --> 01:02:08.480
because I knew Rita was very much capable and very competent

01:02:08.480 --> 01:02:09.080
to run that.

01:02:10.080 --> 01:02:14.760
Holly Springs became a fairly progressive city

01:02:14.760 --> 01:02:20.760
in that they were able to elect the black mayor in the 90s.

01:02:22.120 --> 01:02:27.600
And they were able to work out a kind of coexistence

01:02:27.600 --> 01:02:31.760
with the sheriff and the police chief in that city.

01:02:31.760 --> 01:02:36.440
I understand the police chief has just a bevy of film

01:02:37.120 --> 01:02:40.560
photos from that summer, because he was,

01:02:40.560 --> 01:02:43.560
but he won't release them.

01:02:43.560 --> 01:02:43.840
He won't.

01:02:43.840 --> 01:02:46.680
He's shown to some people who go down and ask about them,

01:02:46.680 --> 01:02:50.080
but I understand he has a treasure trove full of records

01:02:50.080 --> 01:02:51.360
that I can do.

01:02:51.360 --> 01:02:52.040
Right.

01:02:52.040 --> 01:02:57.560
And we have had several reunions, the group from Holly Springs.

01:02:57.560 --> 01:03:03.080
And we have a large number of volunteers who come back.

01:03:03.160 --> 01:03:09.720
We had collected all the material that we had on that notes

01:03:09.720 --> 01:03:13.080
and newsletters and all that kind of thing.

01:03:13.080 --> 01:03:17.640
And we put that, we archived that at Russ College.

01:03:17.640 --> 01:03:20.320
So those records are there with photographs

01:03:20.320 --> 01:03:22.880
and all that, including the reunions.

01:03:22.880 --> 01:03:27.600
And so Larry Rubin was one of the people in that project there.

01:03:27.600 --> 01:03:30.880
And we had a number of people.

01:03:30.880 --> 01:03:35.880
The attorney for President Clinton on the,

01:03:39.960 --> 01:03:42.680
on the, what did they call them?

01:03:42.680 --> 01:03:47.760
They were going, D, what were they going to do with Clinton?

01:03:47.760 --> 01:03:49.000
They were going to take him out of office.

01:03:49.000 --> 01:03:49.840
Oh, go.

01:03:49.840 --> 01:03:50.040
We can teach.

01:03:50.040 --> 01:03:56.040
And Peach, the one that was his private attorney

01:03:56.040 --> 01:03:58.200
was on the project there in Holly Springs.

01:03:58.200 --> 01:04:02.520
So we just chat about those kinds of things

01:04:02.520 --> 01:04:06.360
throughout the years about the various and secondary experience.

01:04:06.360 --> 01:04:11.880
Holly Fry was also a producer, one of the documentary

01:04:11.880 --> 01:04:14.440
zone, Mississippi at Summer.

01:04:14.440 --> 01:04:19.720
He and Connie Field and a couple of others did the movie.

01:04:19.720 --> 01:04:20.920
Where do we go from here?

01:04:20.920 --> 01:04:21.600
Freedom on my mind.

01:04:21.600 --> 01:04:22.440
Freedom on my mind.

01:04:22.440 --> 01:04:22.840
Yes.

01:04:22.840 --> 01:04:24.480
Freedom on my mind.

01:04:25.440 --> 01:04:28.520
And so we've had a lot of very positive things

01:04:28.520 --> 01:04:30.600
come out of that experience in Holly Springs.

01:04:30.600 --> 01:04:33.840
You mentioned the organizing of the Mississippi Freedom

01:04:33.840 --> 01:04:35.800
Democratic Party.

01:04:35.800 --> 01:04:40.320
The idea was to get a representation,

01:04:40.320 --> 01:04:44.400
to go to Atlantic City, to challenge the legitimacy

01:04:44.400 --> 01:04:47.880
of the seating of the all white segregationist party.

01:04:47.880 --> 01:04:51.560
Blacks were not permitted to participate in that.

01:04:51.560 --> 01:04:54.360
Talk a little bit about Atlantic City in your time.

01:04:54.360 --> 01:04:58.240
You're there and your reactions to everything.

01:04:58.240 --> 01:05:00.080
OK.

01:05:00.080 --> 01:05:04.160
The Atlantic City experience was very interesting

01:05:04.160 --> 01:05:09.720
because we managed to box up all of the applications

01:05:09.720 --> 01:05:12.040
that we have received.

01:05:12.040 --> 01:05:18.560
We actually had what we call Watts logs

01:05:18.560 --> 01:05:23.000
on the experiences of that summer, where we kind of documented

01:05:23.000 --> 01:05:26.160
every event that went on.

01:05:26.160 --> 01:05:34.440
We even documented the fact that the Democratic Party

01:05:34.440 --> 01:05:37.240
in the state of Mississippi was not loyal.

01:05:37.240 --> 01:05:42.080
It didn't vote for the Democratic Party ticket

01:05:42.080 --> 01:05:49.280
in presidential election in 1960.

01:05:49.280 --> 01:05:54.160
They didn't just deny blacks an opportunity

01:05:54.160 --> 01:05:56.040
to come to the pre-sanked meetings and all that.

01:05:56.040 --> 01:05:58.120
They usually shifted it away.

01:05:58.120 --> 01:05:59.920
They wouldn't tell you where they were being held

01:05:59.920 --> 01:06:01.280
in some instances.

01:06:01.280 --> 01:06:03.920
And so they were not just discriminatory.

01:06:03.920 --> 01:06:07.920
They just outright said, no, blacks would not be in that.

01:06:07.920 --> 01:06:12.480
The idea was to follow the procedures of the Democratic Party

01:06:12.480 --> 01:06:16.480
and electing delegates to represent the state of Mississippi

01:06:16.480 --> 01:06:17.840
going forward.

01:06:17.840 --> 01:06:21.840
And what we were able to do is we were able to document

01:06:21.840 --> 01:06:24.800
that we followed that procession.

01:06:24.800 --> 01:06:28.200
The pre-sanked meetings, the district meetings,

01:06:28.200 --> 01:06:31.240
the state meeting, and the election of delegations,

01:06:31.240 --> 01:06:35.960
open elections, democratic process, the state chose not

01:06:35.960 --> 01:06:39.360
to use that and made it very clear that they were not going

01:06:39.360 --> 01:06:41.840
to use that.

01:06:41.840 --> 01:06:45.640
I had the pleasure, I guess, of taking the bell off

01:06:45.640 --> 01:06:50.440
of the church in Philadelphia that was burned.

01:06:50.440 --> 01:06:52.920
We put that on top of the truck.

01:06:52.920 --> 01:06:57.360
And we had the burnout station wagon on the back of the truck.

01:06:57.360 --> 01:06:59.320
So we took every visual.

01:06:59.320 --> 01:07:01.680
We were able to get the station wagon from the airport.

01:07:01.680 --> 01:07:03.960
We were able to get to station wagon.

01:07:03.960 --> 01:07:05.400
We put it on the back of the truck.

01:07:05.400 --> 01:07:07.520
And we took both of those things up.

01:07:07.520 --> 01:07:11.120
And we had that on display so people could actually see it.

01:07:11.120 --> 01:07:13.560
And we had a caption on the bottom of it

01:07:13.560 --> 01:07:16.640
and what that actually was.

01:07:16.640 --> 01:07:19.280
Which car was station wagon?

01:07:19.280 --> 01:07:23.040
This was the station wagon that Goodman, Sherry, and Cheney

01:07:23.040 --> 01:07:27.440
were in when they were arrested and later murdered

01:07:27.440 --> 01:07:29.400
in Philadelphia, Mississippi.

01:07:29.400 --> 01:07:33.360
And what happened was they took the station wagon out

01:07:33.360 --> 01:07:36.120
the sheriff and the deputies and the rest of the folk

01:07:36.120 --> 01:07:40.400
took it out to kind of a dirt road.

01:07:40.400 --> 01:07:42.680
And they burned it up.

01:07:42.680 --> 01:07:44.640
And that's what we had.

01:07:44.640 --> 01:07:49.040
So we wanted to let people see the level of violence

01:07:49.040 --> 01:07:56.280
and destruction that people were willing to result to in order

01:07:56.280 --> 01:07:59.880
to maintain the system of segregation.

01:07:59.880 --> 01:08:04.320
And we all set those things up so people could see.

01:08:04.320 --> 01:08:07.440
And we kind of followed the delegation around in order

01:08:07.440 --> 01:08:10.440
to make sure that they could maneuver through whatever

01:08:10.440 --> 01:08:12.520
they needed to maneuver through.

01:08:12.520 --> 01:08:14.560
They would be at the right place at the right time.

01:08:14.560 --> 01:08:20.440
And what we discovered was initially, as the delegates

01:08:20.440 --> 01:08:22.080
moved around other delegates, they

01:08:22.080 --> 01:08:24.360
seemed to get a lot of support.

01:08:24.360 --> 01:08:27.240
And then I think the issue became,

01:08:27.240 --> 01:08:29.720
it began to look like for the Democratic party that it was

01:08:29.720 --> 01:08:33.560
going to be an issue of much larger than what they expected.

01:08:33.560 --> 01:08:35.880
So the Johnson administration decided

01:08:35.880 --> 01:08:41.560
that they needed to have a person in charge of making sure

01:08:41.640 --> 01:08:48.080
that the convention would not be disrupted

01:08:48.080 --> 01:08:51.960
and against the president.

01:08:51.960 --> 01:08:54.480
And so he delegated that responsibility

01:08:54.480 --> 01:08:59.000
to the human humphory, who then delegated it to Walter Mondale.

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:04.200
And they decided that they needed to be a compromise,

01:09:04.200 --> 01:09:07.680
because the delegates from the Mississippi

01:09:07.680 --> 01:09:12.480
and Democratic party was asking to be seated in place of and

01:09:12.480 --> 01:09:13.640
replacing.

01:09:13.640 --> 01:09:16.960
And they were building that on a moral case.

01:09:16.960 --> 01:09:19.000
They were committed to Democratic party.

01:09:19.000 --> 01:09:21.000
They were not discriminatory.

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:24.640
They had a diverse delegation that was there.

01:09:24.640 --> 01:09:30.720
And they wanted to be considered citizens like everybody

01:09:30.720 --> 01:09:31.480
else.

01:09:31.480 --> 01:09:34.520
The issue that they were willing to push for

01:09:34.520 --> 01:09:36.800
is the right to vote for everybody.

01:09:36.800 --> 01:09:40.040
And that they figured that if they had gotten the right to vote,

01:09:40.040 --> 01:09:43.000
that they probably would have been in the ranks of the Democratic

01:09:43.000 --> 01:09:44.040
party.

01:09:44.040 --> 01:09:48.160
So they were loyal in that sense.

01:09:48.160 --> 01:09:57.200
And when the got time to decide on what was going to happen

01:09:57.200 --> 01:10:04.480
with those issues, the Walter Mondale and Humphory came up with the idea

01:10:04.480 --> 01:10:09.000
that they would be granted two seats at large.

01:10:09.000 --> 01:10:12.360
And those with, I think, the majority of the Connecticut

01:10:12.360 --> 01:10:16.440
delegation, they had accepted the fact that they would be there.

01:10:16.440 --> 01:10:24.960
And they came back to the delegation to say that this is what we

01:10:24.960 --> 01:10:26.320
are prepared to give.

01:10:26.320 --> 01:10:29.720
And at that point, the delegation was to meet.

01:10:29.720 --> 01:10:35.880
But before they met, they had this bevy of coalition

01:10:35.880 --> 01:10:39.200
folk from the Marjorne Washington,

01:10:39.200 --> 01:10:46.960
speak to the delegation to try to convince them that that was, in fact, a victory.

01:10:46.960 --> 01:10:55.640
Dr. King and Whitney Young, and somebody from, I can't remember all the names of the

01:10:55.640 --> 01:10:56.640
people.

01:10:56.640 --> 01:11:01.360
And 19 or 20 people that spoke in a church before this delegation.

01:11:01.360 --> 01:11:09.640
But when Johnson actually, President Johnson actually found out that this was going to be

01:11:09.640 --> 01:11:16.120
a serious offense, is when Fannie Lou Hamer spoke.

01:11:16.120 --> 01:11:19.640
And she was about to speak on national TV.

01:11:19.640 --> 01:11:24.880
And at that same moment, he called a press conference that took the press away from

01:11:24.880 --> 01:11:26.200
that.

01:11:26.200 --> 01:11:32.880
And some of the major networks decided to go ahead and run that tape late on that night.

01:11:32.880 --> 01:11:38.360
Because President Johnson didn't have anything to talk about at that particular press conference.

01:11:38.360 --> 01:11:42.840
And that's the speech where Fannie Lou Hamer said, I question America.

01:11:42.840 --> 01:11:52.600
If you don't, you know, seek this democratically elected and selected delegation, where are

01:11:52.600 --> 01:11:55.760
we in America?

01:11:55.760 --> 01:12:05.640
And after the meeting and all that kind of stuff, all of the, I guess, labor, liberal kind

01:12:05.640 --> 01:12:12.360
of folk left, the delegation was sitting there and they had to decide whether or not they

01:12:12.360 --> 01:12:17.320
were going to accept the compromise.

01:12:17.320 --> 01:12:25.640
And after meeting, I think it was Fannie Lou Hamer who said that, you know, we've worked

01:12:25.640 --> 01:12:32.240
too hard and we've come too far to accept that compromise.

01:12:32.240 --> 01:12:37.080
And we came here to be seated and we're not going to be seated.

01:12:37.080 --> 01:12:42.760
And we'll go home and start over again and continue this process to see if we can get

01:12:42.760 --> 01:12:48.880
the Mississippi Freedom Democratic Party represented in the Democratic Party as the legitimate

01:12:48.880 --> 01:12:49.880
entity in the party.

01:12:49.880 --> 01:12:55.760
But you all feel after that you've gone up there, you have been given a compromise that

01:12:55.760 --> 01:12:58.040
wasn't acceptable.

01:12:58.040 --> 01:13:02.520
It was liberal friends in the North and not accommodating.

01:13:02.520 --> 01:13:05.160
Oh no.

01:13:05.160 --> 01:13:10.760
We were very proud about the position taken by the Mississippi delegation, Mississippi Freedom

01:13:10.760 --> 01:13:12.240
Democratic Party delegation.

01:13:12.240 --> 01:13:19.440
But we devastated about the fact that inside of the Democratic Party, morality wasn't

01:13:19.440 --> 01:13:21.800
the basis upon which decisions are made.

01:13:21.800 --> 01:13:25.400
It's power politics at its voice.

01:13:25.400 --> 01:13:26.560
And we hadn't.

01:13:26.560 --> 01:13:32.280
We've still very idealistic about, you know, if we do the right things and if we follow

01:13:32.280 --> 01:13:36.960
the procedures, then good things will happen to you.

01:13:36.960 --> 01:13:38.320
That wasn't the case.

01:13:38.320 --> 01:13:40.440
And so it was devastating.

01:13:40.440 --> 01:13:46.480
And at that point, I think Folk and Snick began to put all of those elements, including

01:13:46.480 --> 01:13:50.280
the Democratic Party to the side, and these are not going to be the vehicles that we can

01:13:50.280 --> 01:13:55.160
ride in order to forget to freedom, justice, and equality.

01:13:55.160 --> 01:14:00.200
And then there was the search on then for where do we go from here in terms of the transition

01:14:00.200 --> 01:14:07.240
from the old line politics of working within the Democratic Party and working within with

01:14:07.240 --> 01:14:10.320
these coalitions that we currently had.

01:14:10.320 --> 01:14:19.320
And so that's when we began to look at the possibility of establishing links with other

01:14:19.320 --> 01:14:26.480
minority groups and see if we could talk about empowerment and self-determination and those

01:14:26.480 --> 01:14:30.280
kinds of issues where we were beginning to look at.

01:14:30.280 --> 01:14:35.960
And we began to move outside of the mainstream of just looking within America.

01:14:35.960 --> 01:14:42.680
We began to look at other movements that were going on in Asia and Africa and South

01:14:42.680 --> 01:14:48.360
America and the West Indies, not the West Indies, but in the South America based in Gulf

01:14:48.360 --> 01:14:50.120
Basin down there.

01:14:50.120 --> 01:14:57.480
And so we began to look at what was going on in Cuba and we began to send people down

01:14:57.480 --> 01:15:05.760
there in Russia and Asia and a number of other places where there were independent movements

01:15:05.760 --> 01:15:13.240
and Mozambique and Guinea-Bassal and Guinea and all those places where movement was actually

01:15:13.240 --> 01:15:14.240
going.

01:15:14.240 --> 01:15:16.040
So SNCC is undergoing some transformation?

01:15:16.040 --> 01:15:17.560
Going through transformation, absolutely.

01:15:17.560 --> 01:15:25.680
And then we have the Selma campaign of 55 SNCC had been in Selma for several years.

01:15:25.680 --> 01:15:32.000
And Martin Luther King and the Southern Christian Leadership Conference chose Selma as the spot

01:15:32.000 --> 01:15:38.880
where they were going to stage demonstrations and push for the passes of the voting rights

01:15:38.880 --> 01:15:39.880
law.

01:15:39.880 --> 01:15:42.680
What did you get to Selma and what did you do there?

01:15:42.680 --> 01:15:51.400
I was in Mississippi as we were having a state MFDP meeting there.

01:15:51.400 --> 01:15:58.560
But before that we had had a staff meeting and the issue of Selma came up.

01:15:58.560 --> 01:16:11.200
And most of us agreed that there was a difference in a strategic difference between SNCC and

01:16:11.200 --> 01:16:19.760
SCLC and that is that we believed in building organization as opposed to mobilizing for some

01:16:19.760 --> 01:16:22.240
particular objective.

01:16:22.240 --> 01:16:31.640
And John raised the question about Selma and he said it was in Alabama and it was close

01:16:31.640 --> 01:16:36.000
to his hometown and that he wanted to participate.

01:16:36.000 --> 01:16:37.000
John Lewis.

01:16:37.000 --> 01:16:38.000
John Lewis.

01:16:38.000 --> 01:16:39.000
Yeah.

01:16:39.000 --> 01:16:45.680
And we took the position that John, we are not going to be engaged in the demonstration

01:16:45.680 --> 01:16:47.200
in Selma.

01:16:47.200 --> 01:16:58.720
But we didn't know of the strategic plan that had been put together between SCLC and Johnson

01:16:58.720 --> 01:17:00.240
administration.

01:17:00.240 --> 01:17:08.600
We didn't know that if that push got going that the voting rights act was going to be tied

01:17:08.600 --> 01:17:11.640
to how effective that was.

01:17:11.640 --> 01:17:21.760
And so we said John you cannot independently because that is what he was talking about as

01:17:21.760 --> 01:17:26.840
chairman of SNCC be a part of this March.

01:17:26.840 --> 01:17:33.600
And John said that he deserved the right to be able to own conscious, be able to go on

01:17:33.600 --> 01:17:34.600
this March.

01:17:34.600 --> 01:17:41.200
And so I think the conclusion was that John, we really don't want you to do this.

01:17:41.200 --> 01:17:46.040
But if you do this we will have some SNCC people there with you.

01:17:46.040 --> 01:17:52.280
So you see Bob Mance is with John on this March.

01:17:52.280 --> 01:18:00.120
And then when John goes over the bridge, John ends up suffering a concussion and is actually

01:18:00.120 --> 01:18:06.280
kind of airlifted out of Selma to Boston and ought to for him to get the hit checked

01:18:06.280 --> 01:18:10.320
out for the concussion and see how severe that was.

01:18:10.320 --> 01:18:20.400
Now anytime anybody in SNCC is ever injured or wounded or is in jail or whatever it is,

01:18:20.400 --> 01:18:25.160
the philosophy of the organization was that we sent somebody in right away.

01:18:25.160 --> 01:18:38.320
And so when we recall in the afternoon of Bloody Sunday, we immediately called together

01:18:38.320 --> 01:18:45.120
some of the people who were at the assembly and found out who had vehicles who could go

01:18:45.120 --> 01:18:47.920
and how many people were going to be in the vehicles.

01:18:47.920 --> 01:18:52.240
And then we launched those people for Selma almost immediately.

01:18:52.240 --> 01:18:57.440
So it was a period of private between and hour and hour and a half before people were

01:18:57.440 --> 01:19:01.960
actually leaving that convention going to Selma.

01:19:01.960 --> 01:19:09.280
And once we got to Selma, Jim was coming down from Atlanta.

01:19:09.280 --> 01:19:10.280
He was flying in.

01:19:10.280 --> 01:19:11.280
I think he got a helicopter.

01:19:11.280 --> 01:19:13.760
Yeah, he got a helicopter.

01:19:13.760 --> 01:19:17.440
Some kind of way he got something to fly into Selma.

01:19:17.440 --> 01:19:18.680
And so we all got there.

01:19:18.680 --> 01:19:20.200
We knew where we were supposed to be going.

01:19:20.200 --> 01:19:28.520
We met there and we were told that there was nothing left to be done.

01:19:28.520 --> 01:19:35.080
We got an update on John and we said the next day we would spread out and begin to work

01:19:35.080 --> 01:19:39.800
through the process of what would be the next steps.

01:19:39.800 --> 01:19:45.720
We were still kind of ambivalent about being there, but the injury that John, that has

01:19:45.720 --> 01:19:47.960
always been an operational principle.

01:19:47.960 --> 01:19:55.600
If one of our, among our ranks had some difficulty, we would rush in and try to provide the

01:19:55.600 --> 01:20:00.720
kind of support and try to continue the work that they were doing until they could either

01:20:00.720 --> 01:20:05.640
recover or we could find a replacement for that.

01:20:05.640 --> 01:20:17.440
I took over the logistical parts and that is trying to work with Hosea Williams and the other logistical

01:20:17.440 --> 01:20:23.200
people in the SCLC where the march was to go.

01:20:23.200 --> 01:20:29.760
And we also brought in Willie "Mukasa" Ricks who could mobilize the young people.

01:20:29.760 --> 01:20:33.600
And so we wanted to keep the pressure on now.

01:20:33.600 --> 01:20:40.320
If we hadn't used all of our resources to build up support for the march, we would.

01:20:40.320 --> 01:20:51.120
And then we had that issue with the injunction to march the injunction from Johnson.

01:20:51.120 --> 01:20:53.720
I think it was federal judge.

01:20:53.720 --> 01:20:59.880
And the question was whether or not Dr. King was going to violate that injunction.

01:20:59.880 --> 01:21:04.640
And I think he concluded that he was going to violate that injunction.

01:21:04.640 --> 01:21:08.760
But when he marched, he marched across the bridge and then turned around and came back

01:21:08.760 --> 01:21:09.760
to the church.

01:21:09.760 --> 01:21:11.720
And that kind of threw everybody off.

01:21:11.720 --> 01:21:16.680
And to be honest with you, it pissed most of the SNCC off because nobody told us what

01:21:16.680 --> 01:21:17.680
the plan was.

01:21:17.680 --> 01:21:21.360
And here we are operating and we don't have a sense of plan.

01:21:21.360 --> 01:21:29.320
So at this point, Jim decides to go down to Montgomery and start another set of demonstrations

01:21:29.320 --> 01:21:31.440
in Montgomery.

01:21:31.440 --> 01:21:36.200
And kind of make sure that we understand that there's a connection between that.

01:21:36.200 --> 01:21:41.760
But we'll do that in Montgomery and create the kind of protest down in Montgomery.

01:21:41.760 --> 01:21:43.920
And that started.

01:21:43.920 --> 01:21:49.520
And we begin to try to work out and try to find out what is going on here.

01:21:49.520 --> 01:21:55.840
And why is it that we are not informed about the objectives?

01:21:55.840 --> 01:21:58.800
And so we kind of worked through that.

01:21:58.800 --> 01:22:03.080
And we got a time and a date that we were actually start out of Selma.

01:22:03.080 --> 01:22:09.400
And we worked logistics out to get the march all the way into Montgomery.

01:22:09.400 --> 01:22:15.320
There is a point in which Jim and some other folks in Montgomery, this is the leadership

01:22:15.320 --> 01:22:16.320
group.

01:22:16.320 --> 01:22:21.080
And Jim is talking about knocking the legs out from under the table if everybody can't

01:22:21.080 --> 01:22:24.160
be equal around that table.

01:22:24.160 --> 01:22:29.760
And I think that it became very clear that there was some missing information and links

01:22:29.760 --> 01:22:31.640
that we didn't have.

01:22:31.640 --> 01:22:37.440
But we figured that once the march got into Selma, that would be over with and we would

01:22:37.440 --> 01:22:39.120
move on.

01:22:39.120 --> 01:22:45.680
And we did not know about Johnson's speech after that about the Voting Rights Act.

01:22:45.680 --> 01:22:51.520
And we shall overcome and then later the passage of the Voting Rights Act.

01:22:51.520 --> 01:22:53.560
So that was kind of tense in there.

01:22:53.560 --> 01:22:57.160
But it wasn't tense because we didn't like people.

01:22:57.160 --> 01:23:04.400
It was tense because we were on different pages about where we were in terms of protests.

01:23:04.400 --> 01:23:10.280
And we had been in Selma for two years prior to SCLC coming in there.

01:23:10.280 --> 01:23:18.520
And we knew that a march would only last maybe 30 days after the march had concluded.

01:23:18.520 --> 01:23:22.280
And that people would dissipate because you haven't organized them into anything.

01:23:22.280 --> 01:23:23.600
And that was our real concern.

01:23:23.600 --> 01:23:25.720
We were trying to build in Selma.

01:23:25.720 --> 01:23:30.840
And we stayed there and we continued and we did build a little something in Selma.

01:23:30.840 --> 01:23:36.560
And that was because we went to the next plan and that is building independent political

01:23:36.560 --> 01:23:37.560
organizations.

01:23:37.560 --> 01:23:44.760
We talked a little bit about Lowndes County, Alabama and how that represented a change for SNCC.

01:23:44.760 --> 01:23:45.760
Right.

01:23:45.760 --> 01:23:48.600
I don't care more about Lounge.

01:23:48.600 --> 01:23:54.960
One of the effects of the Selma march was that Stokely Carmichael Carmichael and others went through

01:23:54.960 --> 01:23:56.880
Lowndes County, Alabama.

01:23:56.880 --> 01:23:59.920
And they started organizing people there.

01:23:59.920 --> 01:24:07.840
And the result was a project for SNCC after that where a number of SNCC field secretaries

01:24:07.840 --> 01:24:12.200
were leaving Mississippi and other projects because they saw something different happening

01:24:12.200 --> 01:24:13.200
there.

01:24:13.200 --> 01:24:16.160
Tell me a little bit about Lowndes County, Alabama in your experience.

01:24:16.160 --> 01:24:17.680
Okay.

01:24:17.680 --> 01:24:24.920
We did go through Lowndes County, Alabama and everywhere we knew that we had to do something a little

01:24:24.920 --> 01:24:30.360
different in terms of a march and not have just a group of people marching down a highway

01:24:30.360 --> 01:24:38.600
that we had to get people along the highway to at least get involved in and actually understand

01:24:38.600 --> 01:24:40.240
what is going on.

01:24:40.240 --> 01:24:43.680
So it was a fertile area.

01:24:43.680 --> 01:24:47.080
It was a part of the Black Belt in Alabama.

01:24:47.080 --> 01:24:53.080
Stokely Carmichael was pretty disenchanted as many of us were with the response that we received

01:24:53.080 --> 01:24:56.960
from the Democratic Party with the challenge.

01:24:56.960 --> 01:25:02.960
And we're looking for other ways in which we could actually organize political power.

01:25:02.960 --> 01:25:08.400
We call it individual, I mean independent political organizing.

01:25:08.400 --> 01:25:12.240
And we were looking at Lowndes County, Alabama, Alabama.

01:25:12.240 --> 01:25:18.200
But we had a pretty healthy and sturdy research department back in Atlanta.

01:25:18.200 --> 01:25:23.760
And Jack Minnis actually goes through the laws in Alabama and he finds that you can

01:25:23.760 --> 01:25:30.400
actually organize an independent party in a particular county in Alabama.

01:25:30.400 --> 01:25:36.280
This was a part of law that was passed during the Civil War era.

01:25:36.280 --> 01:25:43.120
And it said that we could actually go in and organize a separate party in the state of

01:25:43.120 --> 01:25:45.600
Alabama in any county.

01:25:45.600 --> 01:25:49.120
But there were certain requirements that you must go through.

01:25:49.120 --> 01:25:56.600
So we used that to begin to look at organizing in Lowndes County, Alabama and Dallas County and Green

01:25:56.600 --> 01:25:57.600
County.

01:25:57.600 --> 01:25:59.120
And there's another county in Alabama.

01:25:59.120 --> 01:26:01.800
I can't remember what the name of that one is.

01:26:01.800 --> 01:26:05.840
And we started out with Lowndes County, Alabama.

01:26:05.840 --> 01:26:13.440
Now at that point, Snick didn't have the kind of resources it had for 1964.

01:26:13.440 --> 01:26:17.520
The resources have already began to decline.

01:26:17.520 --> 01:26:24.240
And so the job and the task for making resources available fell on me.

01:26:24.240 --> 01:26:34.320
And so what I did was I got other Snickers to go into Lowndes County, Alabama to work along with

01:26:34.320 --> 01:26:37.040
Stokely Carmichael and into other counties.

01:26:37.040 --> 01:26:42.160
And the majority of those folks were the nagged people who had come down the summer of

01:26:42.160 --> 01:26:46.680
1964 who were still working, some in Mississippi and some in other places.

01:26:46.680 --> 01:26:48.240
And we put those in.

01:26:48.240 --> 01:26:56.800
And we got some out of Georgia, Southwest Georgia, to move into that area.

01:26:56.800 --> 01:27:03.000
Because we didn't have a lot of people who transferred in from Mississippi that there.

01:27:03.000 --> 01:27:10.680
Those people that left out of Mississippi generally went home or went on some of the mission.

01:27:10.680 --> 01:27:20.160
But we were also trying to pay down the organization because after the summer of 1964, Snick ended

01:27:20.160 --> 01:27:26.640
up taking in about 70 to 80 of those volunteers.

01:27:26.640 --> 01:27:30.320
And there were a couple of dynamic changes that took place in Snick.

01:27:30.320 --> 01:27:36.680
One was that we got up to a membership that was over 100.

01:27:36.680 --> 01:27:42.040
And we also went from being a predominantly black organization to a predominantly white

01:27:42.040 --> 01:27:43.960
organization.

01:27:43.960 --> 01:27:52.040
And that created some ideological and philosophical concerns in the organization also.

01:27:52.040 --> 01:27:59.040
But what happens is that the stepping up and the escalation of the anti-war movement

01:27:59.040 --> 01:28:04.080
drain off a lot of those folks who were in Snick because that became the exciting kind

01:28:04.080 --> 01:28:14.040
of interface kind of mobilizing that many people began to shift off to.

01:28:14.040 --> 01:28:19.920
But it was Jack who came up with the idea and the plan.

01:28:19.920 --> 01:28:26.120
And we took that plan and went to Lowndes County, Alabama, to Lowndes County, Alabama and organized what was

01:28:26.120 --> 01:28:29.520
called the Lowndes County, Alabama Freedom Organization.

01:28:29.520 --> 01:28:33.800
Same kind of acronym, same kind of freedom that we were talking about.

01:28:33.800 --> 01:28:35.720
But we were talking about empowerment now.

01:28:35.720 --> 01:28:40.320
That was one of the things that came out of Mississippi that people wanted to empower

01:28:40.320 --> 01:28:42.120
themselves.

01:28:42.120 --> 01:28:46.320
And we thought that this was one of the ways in which we could actually do that.

01:28:46.320 --> 01:28:51.640
We were trying to create a new model, another model that could be employed and taken outside

01:28:51.640 --> 01:28:58.440
Lowndes County, Alabama to urban areas and wherever else we were to find those pockets where African

01:28:58.440 --> 01:29:04.960
Americans were the majority and see if we could use that to leverage coalition politics

01:29:04.960 --> 01:29:11.520
with a kind of sound, solid foundation in the African American community.

01:29:11.520 --> 01:29:18.120
So we used limited resources and they began to organize the Lowndes County, Alabama organization

01:29:18.120 --> 01:29:21.920
and the Democratic Party found out what was going on.

01:29:21.920 --> 01:29:29.920
And I think that that influence on the media at that point made people begin to refer

01:29:29.920 --> 01:29:35.280
to the Lowndes County, Alabama Freedom Organization as the Black Panther Party.

01:29:35.280 --> 01:29:38.600
And so that was supposed to be a negative and everybody was supposed to say, oh, this

01:29:38.600 --> 01:29:40.200
is not going to work.

01:29:40.200 --> 01:29:44.880
But for the African American community, that was a very positive kind of thing.

01:29:44.880 --> 01:29:50.320
And so we would, during the period where there were going to be elections and we had organized

01:29:50.320 --> 01:29:55.720
campaigns and actually got people on the ballot and they were running for elections,

01:29:55.720 --> 01:30:06.160
we solicited young men from Philadelphia and Chicago and New York and California to come

01:30:06.160 --> 01:30:12.560
down just to be pole watches and help drive people around and do those kinds of things.

01:30:12.560 --> 01:30:18.000
And so the, many of them came down and when they went back to those respective communities,

01:30:18.000 --> 01:30:22.040
they considered themselves to be the friends of the Black Panther Party.

01:30:22.040 --> 01:30:27.760
And so this is how the notion of Black Panther gets out to California and Chicago and

01:30:27.760 --> 01:30:28.760
in New York.

01:30:28.760 --> 01:30:33.480
And all over these areas, you can find that some kind of organization that's supposed

01:30:33.480 --> 01:30:36.080
to be Black Panthers were created.

01:30:36.080 --> 01:30:43.720
So it's not a, it's not a strain for us to understand that Bobby Sears and Bobby Sears

01:30:43.720 --> 01:30:45.760
was not admitted.

01:30:45.760 --> 01:30:53.160
Use the Lowndes County, Alabama model as the kind of model that they were going to employ in California

01:30:53.160 --> 01:30:59.920
and Oakland to actually empower that particular community and then spread out with the Black

01:30:59.920 --> 01:31:03.080
Panther Party is going in other directions.

01:31:03.080 --> 01:31:09.280
Basically own kind of, it's a standard traditional politics.

01:31:09.280 --> 01:31:16.880
So you were organizing there and elections were held and although blacks were in a majority,

01:31:16.880 --> 01:31:17.880
they did not win.

01:31:17.880 --> 01:31:20.640
What went on with the elections?

01:31:20.640 --> 01:31:26.560
I think that we didn't have the confidence in all of the people in Lowndes County, Alabama to go

01:31:26.560 --> 01:31:27.880
out and vote.

01:31:27.880 --> 01:31:32.760
The next election that was held, they won most of the offices.

01:31:32.760 --> 01:31:37.480
So it was just a matter of going through it the first time around, but you can explain

01:31:37.480 --> 01:31:40.120
that the people who they can actually see.

01:31:40.120 --> 01:31:45.440
One of the things that we always did was SNCC as an organization provided information.

01:31:45.440 --> 01:31:50.240
So we put together these little booklets that people could actually see with Black people

01:31:50.240 --> 01:31:54.760
on the cover in that precinct, Lowndes County, Alabama.

01:31:54.760 --> 01:32:01.480
And we also talked about the role and responsibility for the sheriff, the qualification for a sheriff.

01:32:01.480 --> 01:32:07.320
So that people would feel confident that if they had those very simple qualifications

01:32:07.320 --> 01:32:10.440
that they could be a candidate for that particular office.

01:32:10.440 --> 01:32:20.880
And so it was a defeat because we were just getting people acclimated to the idea of empowerment

01:32:20.880 --> 01:32:25.520
and the importance of the vote and actually in lockstep.

01:32:25.520 --> 01:32:33.880
I think we find that that kind of apprehension was eliminated through these kind of efforts

01:32:33.880 --> 01:32:40.600
back here when you have the 2008 and the 2012 elections with African American vote.

01:32:40.600 --> 01:32:45.960
Because people assume that they was going to still be that kind of apprehension and they

01:32:45.960 --> 01:32:47.960
weren't coming out to vote.

01:32:47.960 --> 01:32:54.040
And I just observed in the 2012 that people, even people who were considered to be those

01:32:54.040 --> 01:33:00.200
will never vote because they have some kind of dereliction or they had some kind of

01:33:00.200 --> 01:33:01.560
issue.

01:33:01.560 --> 01:33:03.560
And they would take that day off.

01:33:03.560 --> 01:33:05.480
It would almost be like the birthday.

01:33:05.480 --> 01:33:08.480
They'd be straight and they'd be in that line.

01:33:08.480 --> 01:33:19.560
And because Obama said to stay until you read to your vote, they were willing to do that.

01:33:19.560 --> 01:33:22.520
All the agitation said, don't go for the okie doke.

01:33:22.520 --> 01:33:23.760
Don't get out of line.

01:33:23.760 --> 01:33:24.760
Stay there to your vote.

01:33:24.760 --> 01:33:27.720
Then after you vote, you're on your own.

01:33:27.720 --> 01:33:33.160
But I think what I'm saying is that, yeah, the first time around, that wasn't successful.

01:33:33.160 --> 01:33:40.560
The second time around, they actually won office and the school board and the city council

01:33:40.560 --> 01:33:45.840
and later mayor, Lowns.

01:33:45.840 --> 01:33:48.960
I can't think of the name of the town in Lowns County.

01:33:48.960 --> 01:33:54.880
But one of the cities in Lowns elected a black mayor and so you began to see that shift

01:33:54.880 --> 01:33:57.000
take place.

01:33:57.000 --> 01:34:09.480
Again, by this time there's an upheaval in, in, in, well, let me just take that one back.

01:34:09.480 --> 01:34:11.560
I'm, I'm thinking too far in advance.

01:34:11.560 --> 01:34:21.960
But what I am, what I'm going is is that while the, the, the election is, is coming back

01:34:21.960 --> 01:34:27.720
around and they're organizing is still going on in, in Alabama.

01:34:27.720 --> 01:34:37.480
One of the things that happens is that, Samuel Younge Jr is killed in, in January 1966 and,

01:34:37.480 --> 01:34:44.160
um, uh, the SNCC responds by putting out a statement against the war in Vietnam.

01:34:44.160 --> 01:34:50.520
And so you began to see that whole notion that I talked about earlier about tying in to,

01:34:50.520 --> 01:34:56.120
becoming more international and tying in to groups that are working on self determination.

01:34:56.120 --> 01:35:01.320
And we see some of that as some of what, what it is that we are trying to, to do and, and

01:35:01.320 --> 01:35:02.800
the community, which we're working.

01:35:02.800 --> 01:35:07.560
We can move here to, uh, and we've taken too much of your time so we're going to wrap

01:35:07.560 --> 01:35:08.560
this up soon.

01:35:08.560 --> 01:35:12.560
But I would like for you to talk about it as you've written about.

01:35:12.560 --> 01:35:18.600
SNCC is undergoing all kinds of changes in, like 1967, it's in a real process.

01:35:18.720 --> 01:35:24.480
When you talk about that and, and your observations as a, as a member of the group.

01:35:24.480 --> 01:35:26.440
Well, there's several things happen.

01:35:26.440 --> 01:35:31.200
One is is that, uh, we had been successful, clearly.

01:35:31.200 --> 01:35:35.040
And success has a tendency to make people move on.

01:35:35.040 --> 01:35:41.160
Uh, and I'm talking about successful in terms of the 1964 Civil Rights Bill, the 1965

01:35:41.160 --> 01:35:45.440
Voting Rights Bill, widespread desegregation.

01:35:45.440 --> 01:35:56.160
You're talking about, um, the, uh, widespread participation in the, in the voting process,

01:35:56.160 --> 01:36:01.720
registering to vote, numbers of people coming out, impoliments of groups that were marginalized

01:36:01.720 --> 01:36:02.800
for a long period of time.

01:36:02.800 --> 01:36:07.080
So these, these are kind of victories that you, that you have to recognize that are taking

01:36:07.080 --> 01:36:08.080
place.

01:36:08.080 --> 01:36:13.200
You can go all the way back through that period with, with the long view of the, of the

01:36:13.200 --> 01:36:19.200
movement and see a number of victories if you put, if you, if you use that perspective.

01:36:19.200 --> 01:36:24.680
Um, the other thing is, is that working in areas like Mississippi and Alabama, where you

01:36:24.680 --> 01:36:34.360
do have the, the shooting in, in, in Lowndes County, Alabama and, um, uh, Rev. James Reeb is, is, uh,

01:36:34.360 --> 01:36:41.640
is kill the seminarian and the other, uh, Catholic, uh, priest is wounded.

01:36:41.640 --> 01:36:50.880
Um, that you can do about two years and after two years, you probably need to, uh, retool

01:36:50.880 --> 01:36:55.560
and, and remove the tapes and all that kind of stuff because you just can't do it.

01:36:55.560 --> 01:36:57.080
It's too much.

01:36:57.080 --> 01:37:04.080
It's, it's too much of an emotional kind of, of, uh, stream that, that's not, not good

01:37:04.080 --> 01:37:08.400
for the, for the, uh, for, for you, for the individual.

01:37:08.400 --> 01:37:12.040
Um, and you began to see other kinds of things happening.

01:37:12.040 --> 01:37:22.080
One is, is that you began to see the emphasis shift away from, um, um, from civil rights

01:37:22.080 --> 01:37:25.560
to the anti-war movement for many young white students.

01:37:25.560 --> 01:37:27.840
And so there's a shifting away there.

01:37:27.840 --> 01:37:37.520
Uh, you also began to see the whole notion about, uh, empowerment, black power, uh, coming

01:37:37.520 --> 01:37:38.840
on.

01:37:38.840 --> 01:37:46.080
And the perception is in how black power is actually projected, comes from a position

01:37:46.080 --> 01:37:49.880
paper of the Atlanta project.

01:37:49.880 --> 01:37:53.400
It was never officially voted on by SNCC.

01:37:53.400 --> 01:38:01.800
It was not the position paper on, um, on black power from SNCC.

01:38:01.800 --> 01:38:08.720
And what happens in that position paper is, as a very narrow view about a kind of black

01:38:08.720 --> 01:38:12.440
white kind of, uh, analysis.

01:38:12.440 --> 01:38:19.840
And, you know, blacks, whites feels superior to blacks and blacks now should put white

01:38:19.880 --> 01:38:21.840
side organization, all that kind of stuff.

01:38:21.840 --> 01:38:28.720
That was never, uh, the basis upon which a black power was brought into, to view.

01:38:28.720 --> 01:38:35.440
Because our assessment and analysis was much larger than just a color, skin color kind

01:38:35.440 --> 01:38:36.760
of analysis.

01:38:36.760 --> 01:38:43.440
And we, we fought that argument, we fought that argument in SNCC, but, uh, the, the, the

01:38:43.440 --> 01:38:47.240
status quo, uh, bought into another idea.

01:38:47.240 --> 01:38:50.600
So many young people were, were moving away.

01:38:50.600 --> 01:38:54.520
Um, we didn't have, newer people coming in, newer people coming in, we didn't have a

01:38:54.520 --> 01:39:00.120
way to educate, uh, those newer people about, even the most recent history.

01:39:00.120 --> 01:39:04.520
So people were coming in, they didn't know anything about the freedom riders in, bail,

01:39:04.520 --> 01:39:10.440
no, um, bail, uh, jail, no bail.

01:39:10.440 --> 01:39:12.800
And, and that whole history and that experience.

01:39:12.800 --> 01:39:19.240
So you had new people coming in and it was just extremely difficult for the organization

01:39:19.240 --> 01:39:20.240
to move forward.

01:39:20.240 --> 01:39:25.360
Plus, we, we, you know, I hear a lot of people that underestimate the impact of co-intail

01:39:25.360 --> 01:39:26.360
probe.

01:39:26.360 --> 01:39:30.920
Co-intail probe had a massive effect in impact on people.

01:39:30.920 --> 01:39:37.280
I ended up in, in prison for three months, uh, during the summer of 1967.

01:39:37.280 --> 01:39:42.600
For, for nothing other than the fact that the judge said that I had, I, I, I was a

01:39:42.600 --> 01:39:48.840
risk and that they were going to deny me bail until Justice Black at the Supreme Court

01:39:48.840 --> 01:39:50.960
said, you got to get them gone.

01:39:50.960 --> 01:39:55.800
This is on my, uh, induction into the military and being found guilty.

01:39:55.800 --> 01:40:00.480
Even though there was never a case and I have never been retried over that case, they

01:40:00.480 --> 01:40:04.960
held me in prison for three months that I don't get any credit for anywhere.

01:40:04.960 --> 01:40:12.480
So those things were real and, and the disruption of families and the, uh, credibility,

01:40:12.480 --> 01:40:17.000
and the character assassination and all that was, was going on.

01:40:17.000 --> 01:40:21.760
So these are the things that I think caused, uh, somewhat of the demise of the movement.

01:40:21.760 --> 01:40:23.360
It was never a black power.

01:40:23.360 --> 01:40:28.720
It was never a conflict between SNCC and, and, and Dr. King.

01:40:28.720 --> 01:40:35.160
And, you know, I was, and, and this is where I want to at least say this and we go write

01:40:35.160 --> 01:40:37.480
it and we go and document it and all.

01:40:37.480 --> 01:40:41.840
But when (David) Garrow did his book back on King, uh, he came and he ended up in prison for a

01:40:41.880 --> 01:40:45.680
time and he came and he interviewed me and I said, (David) Garrow, I want to tell you something

01:40:45.680 --> 01:40:52.840
that happened, uh, shortly after Cicero, Illinois, Dr. King came back to Atlanta.

01:40:52.840 --> 01:40:54.360
I, I went back to Atlanta.

01:40:54.360 --> 01:41:02.200
Dr. King asked, Stokeley, Rick's and myself to come by the house.

01:41:02.200 --> 01:41:08.240
He wanted to just have us over for dinner and he had us down in the basement.

01:41:08.240 --> 01:41:14.240
And we stayed there for maybe four or five hours and he said, I want to understand black

01:41:14.240 --> 01:41:15.240
power.

01:41:15.240 --> 01:41:18.800
I want to understand what you're saying about black power.

01:41:18.800 --> 01:41:22.240
And we went through that and we went through the history and he said, but what about

01:41:22.240 --> 01:41:23.880
this and what about that?

01:41:23.880 --> 01:41:33.440
He asked all the questions that he wanted to have answered and he says that, okay, I am

01:41:33.480 --> 01:41:39.800
not going to be a, as an organizational person, we are not going to be able to endorse and

01:41:39.800 --> 01:41:42.680
support black power, okay?

01:41:42.680 --> 01:41:45.120
We just can't do that.

01:41:45.120 --> 01:41:53.440
And we said, okay, but because you can't, then we have to agree that neither of us will

01:41:53.440 --> 01:41:59.120
find ourselves in a situation where we condemn one another and we're going to all be able

01:41:59.120 --> 01:42:02.920
to go down the same street and we'll all be very supportive.

01:42:02.920 --> 01:42:08.920
And we kind of shook hands on that because he said, now explain to me where you're coming

01:42:08.920 --> 01:42:15.440
from and what you're saying and is this just a hatred of whites and all that kind of

01:42:15.440 --> 01:42:18.200
stuff we explain that we're not even talking about that.

01:42:18.200 --> 01:42:25.160
We're talking about empowerment of black tying our movement to movements outside and all

01:42:25.240 --> 01:42:29.040
that kind of stuff and that's where we come from.

01:42:29.040 --> 01:42:34.160
You know our history, you know how we have gone through this experience.

01:42:34.160 --> 01:42:43.880
And I think in the, from chaos to community, Dr. Kang says that there were some people

01:42:43.880 --> 01:42:48.160
who articulated black power that were okay, but there were others who got it all screwed

01:42:48.160 --> 01:42:49.160
up.

01:42:49.160 --> 01:42:55.040
And I think that that is the time when he makes a reference to this meeting in our agreement

01:42:55.040 --> 01:43:03.640
because there was never a moment in which there was a antagonism between Stokely Carmichael and Dr.

01:43:03.640 --> 01:43:04.640
Kang.

01:43:04.640 --> 01:43:12.720
Matter of fact, when Dr. Kang came out in 67 with his position against the war in Vietnam,

01:43:12.720 --> 01:43:21.320
he called and asked Stokely Carmichael and I to come to that Sunday morning meeting and Stokely Carmichael

01:43:21.320 --> 01:43:23.600
said, but you know I'm a heathen.

01:43:23.600 --> 01:43:27.960
He said, bring your butt on anyhow because I have something I want to say and we got

01:43:27.960 --> 01:43:28.960
there.

01:43:28.960 --> 01:43:29.960
We want the front.

01:43:29.960 --> 01:43:30.960
Oh yeah.

01:43:30.960 --> 01:43:31.960
Oh yeah.

01:43:31.960 --> 01:43:37.560
So I'm there and I'm listening and he goes, you know, and I said, and that's what we asked

01:43:37.560 --> 01:43:38.880
you to do all the time.

01:43:38.880 --> 01:43:41.920
You know we kept telling you that there was a moral basis.

01:43:41.920 --> 01:43:47.280
I was more political and we understand, you know, but you have to deal with that on a

01:43:47.280 --> 01:43:48.600
moral basis.

01:43:48.600 --> 01:43:56.160
So that is missed sometimes and you know and people keep the myth going about these other

01:43:56.160 --> 01:43:57.160
kinds of things.

01:43:57.160 --> 01:44:06.080
Now, (David) Garrow said that he couldn't find among other lieutenants of Dr. Kang a confirmation

01:44:06.080 --> 01:44:07.080
of that meeting.

01:44:07.080 --> 01:44:12.080
I said, I guess he thought I made it up, but I think that's pivocal.

01:44:12.080 --> 01:44:15.400
You know, it's a fascinating piece of theory.

01:44:15.400 --> 01:44:17.800
And you know, I talked to Willa Rick all the time.

01:44:17.800 --> 01:44:23.360
I talked to Kwame about that before he died and I said, you know, that's that's the

01:44:23.360 --> 01:44:26.000
part of the history we need to make sure is kept.

01:44:26.000 --> 01:44:32.480
But if you read Kwame's autobiography, you know, he actually talks about the friendship

01:44:32.480 --> 01:44:33.760
and the finance.

01:44:33.760 --> 01:44:44.360
When Dr. Kang goes to what is Resurrection City, was it Resurrection City?

01:44:44.360 --> 01:44:52.600
I was after he was in Washington, I think, setting up for that kind of thing.

01:44:52.600 --> 01:44:57.800
And he was having problems with the black militants up there.

01:44:57.800 --> 01:45:02.560
And he said, it's the Stokely Carmichael, I need some help with this.

01:45:02.560 --> 01:45:03.560
And he said, what you need?

01:45:03.560 --> 01:45:06.840
And he said, I need for these people to back off a few minutes.

01:45:06.840 --> 01:45:10.400
Because what's happening is they're creating so much conflict that I can't give a message

01:45:10.400 --> 01:45:12.120
out about poverty.

01:45:12.120 --> 01:45:15.640
And so he said, okay, and he went around and he talked to all those groups, called them

01:45:15.640 --> 01:45:20.640
all again and said, if you all don't want to be in bomb with this program to Dr. Kang,

01:45:20.640 --> 01:45:22.440
then don't go.

01:45:22.440 --> 01:45:24.280
But leave him alone.

01:45:24.280 --> 01:45:34.320
And so they still had that kind of working relationship, even as we were moving closer

01:45:34.320 --> 01:45:36.280
to Memphis and his assassination.

01:45:36.280 --> 01:45:38.600
Wow, this is all about fascinating stuff.

01:45:38.600 --> 01:45:40.560
I think we're going to have to come back.

01:45:40.560 --> 01:45:43.120
If you are willing.

01:45:43.120 --> 01:45:54.600
What we have here is a period when you personally were undergoing much stress with the being

01:45:54.600 --> 01:46:02.000
jailed for refusing the draft, the organizing at Orangeburg, the Orangeburg massacre,

01:46:02.000 --> 01:46:07.080
where you were incarcerated there, you were broke.

01:46:07.080 --> 01:46:15.720
You had limited resources and yet you came back and you devoted yourself to career and

01:46:15.720 --> 01:46:16.720
education.

01:46:16.720 --> 01:46:21.120
You got your master's in Harvard, your doctorate at UNC.

01:46:21.120 --> 01:46:24.320
Tell us briefly what you've been doing these last 40 years.

01:46:24.320 --> 01:46:30.560
Well, what I've been doing these last 40 years is enjoying one of the most unique experiences

01:46:30.560 --> 01:46:31.560
that I've ever had.

01:46:31.560 --> 01:46:38.400
And that was being a member of a situation that was almost like a university setting where

01:46:38.400 --> 01:46:44.400
I had contact with the Archibald coxies of the world, and Dr. Kang and Whitney Youngs

01:46:44.400 --> 01:46:54.680
and Malcolm X and Ella Baker and Fandall Hamlin and Ruby Dyer's Robinson and a collective

01:46:54.680 --> 01:46:58.640
of individuals who made a difference in this world.

01:46:59.120 --> 01:47:03.320
I got an education that I could not have gotten under any other circumstance.

01:47:03.320 --> 01:47:09.720
And so I'm trying to share that with the community from which I have come and share that with

01:47:09.720 --> 01:47:15.120
the community that's still interested in knowing about the courage and determination of these

01:47:15.120 --> 01:47:16.120
legends.

01:47:16.120 --> 01:47:18.120
I stand on the show of them.

01:47:18.120 --> 01:47:19.120
I'm very proud of them.

01:47:19.120 --> 01:47:21.720
I want to represent them.

01:47:21.720 --> 01:47:25.200
I want to be able to tell my story and tell their story too.

01:47:25.200 --> 01:47:29.440
As in telling my always include them in that whole process.

01:47:29.440 --> 01:47:31.520
Part of your story is your autobiography.

01:47:31.520 --> 01:47:32.680
The copy is right there.

01:47:32.680 --> 01:47:36.000
People that up, the river of no return.

01:47:36.000 --> 01:47:39.440
It was published 40 years ago.

01:47:39.440 --> 01:47:44.320
And I still think that it is in terms of movement autobiographies.

01:47:44.320 --> 01:47:47.920
This is the most insightful and honest I have read.

01:47:47.920 --> 01:47:50.480
So people watching this are reading the transcript.

01:47:50.480 --> 01:47:52.000
Pick up this book.

01:47:52.000 --> 01:47:55.600
And you will get even more of the story.

01:47:55.600 --> 01:47:57.720
Dr. Seller, thank you very much.

01:47:57.720 --> 01:48:01.200
We are indebted to you for sharing your insights with us.

01:48:01.200 --> 01:48:02.200
OK.

01:48:02.200 --> 01:48:03.200
Thank you very much.

01:48:03.200 --> 01:48:07.040
And I'm glad to be able to get the latter part into this film.

01:48:07.040 --> 01:48:08.040
Yeah.

01:48:08.040 --> 01:48:10.280
I know that.

01:48:10.280 --> 01:48:15.560
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum

01:48:15.560 --> 01:48:18.000
of African American History and Culture.

